 "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "66d4f86540679673a8a2c10b483a1cc233e268bacfe3cb9a99f55aa885c120b9", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "by the Comit\u00e9 sectoriel de main-d\u2019\u0153uvre (CSMO), as well as our article \n\u201cHow to Make Your AGM Great, Not Just Necessary\u201d \n1\n2\n3\n4\n7\n7\n9\n11\n12\n12\n15\n17\n1  Why we hold general meetings................................................................................................\n2  Finding the rules that apply to you..........................................................................................\n3  When to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM) .............................................................\n4  When to have a Special General Meeting (SGM)...................................................................\n5  Where to hold your meeting.....................................................................................................\n6  Setting the agenda....................................................................................................................\n7  Giving notice of the meeting.....................................................................................................\n8  Quorum.....................................................................................................................................\n9  Minutes......................................................................................................................................\n10  Meeting Procedure..................................................................................................................\n11  Presenting financial statements..............................................................................................\n12  Board elections........................................................................................................................", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1363, "end_char_idx": 3093, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c367bbf7-45e6-488a-8ee0-d590e3c558a0": {"__data__": {"id_": "c367bbf7-45e6-488a-8ee0-d590e3c558a0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section provides information on the importance of holding general meetings, finding applicable rules, determining the timing for Annual General Meetings (AGM) and Special General Meetings (SGM), selecting a location for the meeting, setting the agenda, giving notice, establishing quorum, recording minutes, following meeting procedures, presenting financial statements, and conducting board elections. The content is likely sourced from the Comit\u00e9 sectoriel de main-d\u2019\u0153uvre (CSMO) and includes guidance on making AGMs effective and not just a necessary obligation.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of following the rules outlined in an organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and it sets out basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. By-laws may also contain rules for running general meetings. Samples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations are provided in resources listed at the end of the document. For federally incorporated organizations, model by-laws and a by-laws builder are offered by Corporations Canada.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of knowing whether your non-profit organization is provincially or federally incorporated, as well as the rules set out in your organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and location.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the key differences between provincially incorporated non-profits in Quebec and federally incorporated non-profits in terms of the rules they must follow?\n2. How can non-profit organizations determine whether they are provincially or federally incorporated, and what implications does this have for their governance and operations?\n3. What specific information is typically included in a non-profit organization's constitution, and how does it differ from the organization's by-laws in terms of setting out rules and guidelines for governance?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "60e5b871-41cd-4c67-9db9-2cd99c399ad6", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "cfb06b29673d271833f495c9d5e3d45f5aea1e5a90d518d6af07a064183d66f0", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "622a5e29-7275-4d83-ad0f-54d591ef0f83", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "d50d4a7ddfb952702ba1e8d4d6d1d4a7e2022f927bcac341caf321d9a7628f5d", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "2\n2  Finding the rules that apply to you\nTo use this info-sheet, you will need to know whether your non-profit is provincially incorporated in Quebec \n(under Part III of Quebec\u2019s Companies Act ) or federally incorporated (under the Canada Not-for-Profit \nCorporations Act). For more information on types of non-profits , see COCo\u2019S info-sheet on  Incorporation \nof a Non-Profit in Quebec. \nThe other important set of rules that apply to you are the rules set out in your organization\u2019s \nconstitution and its by-laws. \nThis information sheet uses \u201cconstitution\u201d to mean the document that was issued by the government to \ncertify your organization\u2019s creation. The constitution is often likened to the organization\u2019s \u201cbirth certificate\u201d. \nThe technical name for your constitution is either letters patent, if you are a provincially incorporated non-\nprofit under the Quebec Companies Act; or  articles of incorporation , if you are a federally incorporated \nnon-profit.\nYour constitution sets out some basic rules for your organization including its name, its purpose, and the \nlocation of", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1086, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "622a5e29-7275-4d83-ad0f-54d591ef0f83": {"__data__": {"id_": "622a5e29-7275-4d83-ad0f-54d591ef0f83", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of knowing whether your non-profit organization is provincially or federally incorporated, as well as the rules set out in your organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and location.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of having a constitution for a federally incorporated non-profit organization, which outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. It also mentions the significance of having valid by-laws, providing samples for provincially incorporated organizations and resources for federally incorporated organizations. The section emphasizes the need to adapt these samples to fit the organization's needs while remaining consistent with the constitution and the law. Examples of common rules adopted by non-profits in their by-laws are also provided.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of following the rules outlined in an organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and it sets out basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. By-laws may also contain rules for running general meetings. Samples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations are provided in resources listed at the end of the document. For federally incorporated organizations, model by-laws and a by-laws builder are offered by Corporations Canada.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the basic rules outlined in an organization's constitution, and how do they differ for provincially and federally incorporated non-profit organizations?\n2. Where can samples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations be found, and what resources are available for federally incorporated organizations in terms of by-laws?\n3. How does the document define a constitution in the context of a non-profit organization, and what is the significance of having valid by-laws for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "60e5b871-41cd-4c67-9db9-2cd99c399ad6", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "cfb06b29673d271833f495c9d5e3d45f5aea1e5a90d518d6af07a064183d66f0", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "c367bbf7-45e6-488a-8ee0-d590e3c558a0", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "9c2bf91dda5eb56116b5cbdaa34451cf9e60c61825ccd7fa1820116d5088cb3e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "5c3fe95d-d7d8-4d55-867e-e4890f2c1214", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "29ec705c20c7f5038b0cc5f8d50975234661bfd487ffb031f7ca313355299903", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "that apply to you are the rules set out in your organization\u2019s \nconstitution and its by-laws. \nThis information sheet uses \u201cconstitution\u201d to mean the document that was issued by the government to \ncertify your organization\u2019s creation. The constitution is often likened to the organization\u2019s \u201cbirth certificate\u201d. \nThe technical name for your constitution is either letters patent, if you are a provincially incorporated non-\nprofit under the Quebec Companies Act; or  articles of incorporation , if you are a federally incorporated \nnon-profit.\nYour constitution sets out some basic rules for your organization including its name, its purpose, and the \nlocation of its office. It may also contain rules that affect how you run your general meetings.\nSamples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations can be found in the resources listed \nat the end, including Votre association (at pages 84 and following) and the Bo\u00eete \u00e0 outils,  2016 (in the \nappendices referenced by Module 1). \nFor federally incorporated organizations, Corporations Canada offers model by-laws and a by-laws builder", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 423, "end_char_idx": 1527, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5c3fe95d-d7d8-4d55-867e-e4890f2c1214": {"__data__": {"id_": "5c3fe95d-d7d8-4d55-867e-e4890f2c1214", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of following the rules outlined in an organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and it sets out basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. By-laws may also contain rules for running general meetings. Samples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations are provided in resources listed at the end of the document. For federally incorporated organizations, model by-laws and a by-laws builder are offered by Corporations Canada.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, providing guidance on how to create and adapt them to suit the organization's needs. It mentions the availability of model by-laws and a by-laws builder tool for federally incorporated organizations. The section also highlights examples of rules commonly found in non-profit by-laws, such as requirements for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities. By-laws are described as internal rules that govern how the organization operates, particularly in relation to membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of having a constitution for a federally incorporated non-profit organization, which outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. It also mentions the significance of having valid by-laws, providing samples for provincially incorporated organizations and resources for federally incorporated organizations. The section emphasizes the need to adapt these samples to fit the organization's needs while remaining consistent with the constitution and the law. Examples of common rules adopted by non-profits in their by-laws are also provided.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are some examples of rules commonly found in non-profit by-laws, such as requirements for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities?\n2. Where can federally incorporated non-profit organizations find model by-laws and a by-laws builder tool to help create and adapt their by-laws to suit their organization's needs?\n3. How can organizations ensure that their by-laws remain consistent with the contents of their constitution and the law while adapting them to fit their specific needs, spirit, and practices?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys