dix. It is best to adapt these samples to the \nneeds, spirit, and practices of your own organization, so long as they remain consistent with the contents of \nyour constitution and the law.. Examples of rules that non-profits commonly adopt in their by-laws are also \nprovided throughout this info-sheet, for example:\n Organizations who aim to ensure their decisions are made by the people directly impacted by their", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 921, "end_char_idx": 2011, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c67fadbf-20e4-42e6-9c59-2d1331e6e954": {"__data__": {"id_": "c67fadbf-20e4-42e6-9c59-2d1331e6e954", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of having a constitution for a federally incorporated non-profit organization, which outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. It also mentions the significance of having valid by-laws, providing samples for provincially incorporated organizations and resources for federally incorporated organizations. The section emphasizes the need to adapt these samples to fit the organization's needs while remaining consistent with the constitution and the law. Examples of common rules adopted by non-profits in their by-laws are also provided.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, which are internal rules that govern how the organization operates. By-laws cover aspects such as membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. They are different from organizational policies, which address day-to-day issues. By-laws must be approved by the membership and comply with the organization's constitution and the law under which it is incorporated. The section also mentions the requirement for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities to ensure decisions are made by those directly impacted.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, providing guidance on how to create and adapt them to suit the organization's needs. It mentions the availability of model by-laws and a by-laws builder tool for federally incorporated organizations. The section also highlights examples of rules commonly found in non-profit by-laws, such as requirements for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities. By-laws are described as internal rules that govern how the organization operates, particularly in relation to membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can non-profit organizations adapt model by-laws provided by Corporations Canada to suit their own needs while remaining consistent with their constitution and the law?\n2. What are some examples of rules commonly found in non-profit by-laws, such as requirements for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities?\n3. How do by-laws differ from organizational policies in non-profit organizations, and what specific aspects do they typically cover, such as membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "60e5b871-41cd-4c67-9db9-2cd99c399ad6", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "cfb06b29673d271833f495c9d5e3d45f5aea1e5a90d518d6af07a064183d66f0", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "5c3fe95d-d7d8-4d55-867e-e4890f2c1214", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "6a3d6825df439622f342f62cf4f74b94f2b2a8807b6273909260ae9fd0b1a474", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "4d2b3101-3f19-4b3f-a7af-f5bbca645a3a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "23993aec2f14f0916d4b250187b80deb3f1ee3f39a0172c75e7c316188d3e16e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "the \nappendices referenced by Module 1). \nFor federally incorporated organizations, Corporations Canada offers model by-laws and a by-laws builder \ntool on its website; we have included the link to that in the appendix. It is best to adapt these samples to the \nneeds, spirit, and practices of your own organization, so long as they remain consistent with the contents of \nyour constitution and the law.. Examples of rules that non-profits commonly adopt in their by-laws are also \nprovided throughout this info-sheet, for example:\n Organizations who aim to ensure their decisions are made by the people directly impacted by their \n work or who aim to foster leadership within their constituencies will sometimes adopt by-laws \n requiring that a given proportion of its directors have participated in the organization\u2019s activities.\nOne level below the constitution is your non-profit's by-laws which are internal rules your or -\nganization makes for itself about how it operates. By-laws often describe rules that must be \nfollowed for membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. By-laws are different \nfrom organizational policies,", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1381, "end_char_idx": 2527, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4d2b3101-3f19-4b3f-a7af-f5bbca645a3a": {"__data__": {"id_": "4d2b3101-3f19-4b3f-a7af-f5bbca645a3a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, providing guidance on how to create and adapt them to suit the organization's needs. It mentions the availability of model by-laws and a by-laws builder tool for federally incorporated organizations. The section also highlights examples of rules commonly found in non-profit by-laws, such as requirements for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities. By-laws are described as internal rules that govern how the organization operates, particularly in relation to membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses when to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM) if you are provincially incorporated. It mentions that provincially incorporated non-profits must hold their AGM at a time allowed by their letters patent and by-laws, or on the fourth Wednesday in January at their head office if no specific time is set. It also explains the concept of a fiscal year and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it highlights the importance of holding the AGM within four months of the end of the organization's financial year to comply with legal requirements regarding financial statements.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, which are internal rules that govern how the organization operates. By-laws cover aspects such as membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. They are different from organizational policies, which address day-to-day issues. By-laws must be approved by the membership and comply with the organization's constitution and the law under which it is incorporated. The section also mentions the requirement for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities to ensure decisions are made by those directly impacted.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can non-profit organizations ensure that decisions are made by individuals directly impacted by their work?\n2. What is the difference between by-laws and organizational policies in non-profit organizations?\n3. How can non-profit organizations ensure that their by-laws are binding and compliant with their constitution and the law under which they are incorporated?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "60e5b871-41cd-4c67-9db9-2cd99c399ad6", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "cfb06b29673d271833f495c9d5e3d45f5aea1e5a90d518d6af07a064183d66f0", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "c67fadbf-20e4-42e6-9c59-2d1331e6e954", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "150c5f50b3a1ecfba390509ae60b5f3b9e155093543cae18936bf14fdd269bea", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "are also \nprovided throughout this info-sheet, for example:\n Organizations who aim to ensure their decisions are made by the people directly impacted by their \n work or who aim to foster leadership within their constituencies will sometimes adopt by-laws \n requiring that a given proportion of its directors have participated in the organization\u2019s activities.\nOne level below the constitution is your non-profit's by-laws which are internal rules your or -\nganization makes for itself about how it operates. By-laws often describe rules that must be \nfollowed for membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. By-laws are different \nfrom organizational policies, which tend to address day-to-day issues like hiring, sick- and va -\ncation-time, and purchasing. Changes to your by-laws must be approved by your membership, \nwhile policies can simply be adopted by the board or staff. For by-laws to be binding, they have \nto comply with your constitution and with the law under which you are incorporated.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1853, "end_char_idx": 2868, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8eadf4d6-22b7-4f97-9cda-26c898111b68": {"__data__": {"id_": "8eadf4d6-22b7-4f97-9cda-26c898111b68", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, which are internal rules that govern how the organization operates. By-laws cover aspects such as membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. They are different from organizational policies, which address day-to-day issues. By-laws must be approved by the membership and comply with the organization's constitution and the law under which it is incorporated. The section also mentions the requirement for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities to ensure decisions are made by those directly impacted.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the timing of Annual General Meetings (AGMs) and the importance of holding them within four months of the organization's financial year end. It also explains what a fiscal year is and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it mentions that some organizations have a fixed date for their AGM stated in their by-laws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses when to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM) if you are provincially incorporated. It mentions that provincially incorporated non-profits must hold their AGM at a time allowed by their letters patent and by-laws, or on the fourth Wednesday in January at their head office if no specific time is set. It also explains the concept of a fiscal year and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it highlights the importance of holding the AGM within four months of the end of the organization's financial year to comply with legal requirements regarding financial statements.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for when a provincially incorporated non-profit organization must hold their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. How does the concept of a fiscal year relate to budgeting spending and income for organizations?\n3. Why is it important for financial statements presented at the AGM to have been approved within the last four months?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "e26213ae-5046-4ec1-933c-183e3635d301", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "aa2944ea8c30599d38ac57b7ac372a7727cd7008bd313362ad9940af58e148c6", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "865a2a9c-caed-42cb-b2ef-2739c461704c", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "4f554a8256004fb3e49df1a78b0091e974483e818ac40f804b3a9643e870062a", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "3\n3  When to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM)\nIf you are provincially incorporated...  \nProvincially incorporated non-profits must hold their Annual General Meeting each year at a time allowed \nby your letters patent and your by-laws. If none is set, your AGM must be held on the fourth Wednesday in \nJanuary at their head office.\n It\u2019s common for the by-laws of provincially incorporated non-profits to provide that their AGM must \nbe held within four months of the end of the organization\u2019s financial year. This allows flexibility in timing your \nAGM, and also makes it easier to satisfy the legal requirement that financial statements presented at the \nAGM must have been approved within the last four months. See below in Section 11 \n                 -- Presenting financial statements for more information. \n?\nWhat is a Fiscal year? \nA fiscal (or financial) year, is the year an organization uses to budget its \nspending and income. Fiscal years are not the same from", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 978, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "865a2a9c-caed-42cb-b2ef-2739c461704c": {"__data__": {"id_": "865a2a9c-caed-42cb-b2ef-2739c461704c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses when to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM) if you are provincially incorporated. It mentions that provincially incorporated non-profits must hold their AGM at a time allowed by their letters patent and by-laws, or on the fourth Wednesday in January at their head office if no specific time is set. It also explains the concept of a fiscal year and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it highlights the importance of holding the AGM within four months of the end of the organization's financial year to comply with legal requirements regarding financial statements.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of fiscal (or financial) year, which is the year an organization uses to budget its spending and income. It explains that fiscal years vary from organization to organization, with examples of fiscal years running from January 1st to December 31st or April 1st to March 31st. The section also mentions the importance of having a fixed date for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) in the organization's bylaws, with examples of fixed dates or approximate timeframes for holding the AGM within four months of the end of the fiscal year.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the timing of Annual General Meetings (AGMs) and the importance of holding them within four months of the organization's financial year end. It also explains what a fiscal year is and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it mentions that some organizations have a fixed date for their AGM stated in their by-laws.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the timing of an organization's Annual General Meeting (AGM) relate to its financial year end and the approval of financial statements?\n2. What is the significance of having a fixed date for the AGM stated in an organization's by-laws?\n3. How do organizations use fiscal years to budget their spending and income, and how does this vary between different organizations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "e26213ae-5046-4ec1-933c-183e3635d301", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "aa2944ea8c30599d38ac57b7ac372a7727cd7008bd313362ad9940af58e148c6", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "8eadf4d6-22b7-4f97-9cda-26c898111b68", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "9ab3ccef05d4897dfe6efba9089906678509943dade2c99fc65b7ceaf466f4a3", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "2659ee8f-a62c-4a5a-8788-0849de5207fc", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "7b5282d828393fb35912fdbfb5e7ee78b8d08eed1778949b0a7239a5561b680e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "must \nbe held within four months of the end of the organization\u2019s financial year. This allows flexibility in timing your \nAGM, and also makes it easier to satisfy the legal requirement that financial statements presented at the \nAGM must have been approved within the last four months. See below in Section 11 \n                 -- Presenting financial statements for more information. \n?\nWhat is a Fiscal year? \nA fiscal (or financial) year, is the year an organization uses to budget its \nspending and income. Fiscal years are not the same from organization to \norganization. At COCo, many non-profits that we work with have fiscal years \nthat run either from January 1st to December 31st, or April 1st to March 31st.\n!\nSome organizations have a fixed date in their by-laws for their AGM.\n For example, an organization could state that their AGM will be held  \n on March 2nd of every year, so long as this was within four months of", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 433, "end_char_idx": 1365, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2659ee8f-a62c-4a5a-8788-0849de5207fc": {"__data__": {"id_": "2659ee8f-a62c-4a5a-8788-0849de5207fc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the timing of Annual General Meetings (AGMs) and the importance of holding them within four months of the organization's financial year end. It also explains what a fiscal year is and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it mentions that some organizations have a fixed date for their AGM stated in their by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations regarding their Annual General Meeting (AGM) and Special General Meeting (SGM). Key topics include the timing of AGMs, the consequences of not holding AGMs as required by federal law, and the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM at any time. The section also mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates within which AGMs must be called. Key entities mentioned are federally incorporated non-profit organizations and interested persons who can apply for the dissolution of an organization that fails to hold AGMs as required.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of fiscal (or financial) year, which is the year an organization uses to budget its spending and income. It explains that fiscal years vary from organization to organization, with examples of fiscal years running from January 1st to December 31st or April 1st to March 31st. The section also mentions the importance of having a fixed date for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) in the organization's bylaws, with examples of fixed dates or approximate timeframes for holding the AGM within four months of the end of the fiscal year.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are some examples of fiscal years used by non-profit organizations, and how do they vary from organization to organization?\n2. How do some organizations ensure the timing of their Annual General Meetings (AGMs) aligns with the end of their fiscal year, as mentioned in their by-laws?\n3. What are the consequences for federally incorporated non-profit organizations if they fail to hold their AGMs as required by federal law, and who has the authority to call a Special General Meeting (SGM) in such cases?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "e26213ae-5046-4ec1-933c-183e3635d301", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "aa2944ea8c30599d38ac57b7ac372a7727cd7008bd313362ad9940af58e148c6", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "865a2a9c-caed-42cb-b2ef-2739c461704c", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "091f0c841ee0dad092bbcef065e9656bd5f84f8fff1ca30d68b4ee4785e7ea8a", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "fiscal (or financial) year, is the year an organization uses to budget its \nspending and income. Fiscal years are not the same from organization to \norganization. At COCo, many non-profits that we work with have fiscal years \nthat run either from January 1st to December 31st, or April 1st to March 31st.\n!\nSome organizations have a fixed date in their by-laws for their AGM.\n For example, an organization could state that their AGM will be held  \n on March 2nd of every year, so long as this was within four months of  \n the end of their fiscal year. \nSome organizations do not have a fixed date in their bylaws, but their \nbylaws say approximately when their AGM will be held: \n For example, an organization could state in their bylaws that their   \n AGM occurs between the third week of February and the third week \n of March, so long as this was within four months of the end of their  \n fiscal year.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 847, "end_char_idx": 1751, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1e4b0c7f-5e29-432a-8294-7f71fb03c15b": {"__data__": {"id_": "1e4b0c7f-5e29-432a-8294-7f71fb03c15b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of fiscal (or financial) year, which is the year an organization uses to budget its spending and income. It explains that fiscal years vary from organization to organization, with examples of fiscal years running from January 1st to December 31st or April 1st to March 31st. The section also mentions the importance of having a fixed date for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) in the organization's bylaws, with examples of fixed dates or approximate timeframes for holding the AGM within four months of the end of the fiscal year.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) and a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains the consequences of not holding an AGM, the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM, and the importance of addressing emergent issues or decisions that require a formal vote. Additionally, it mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates for AGMs and provides information on the required proportion of votes for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations regarding their Annual General Meeting (AGM) and Special General Meeting (SGM). Key topics include the timing of AGMs, the consequences of not holding AGMs as required by federal law, and the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM at any time. The section also mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates within which AGMs must be called. Key entities mentioned are federally incorporated non-profit organizations and interested persons who can apply for the dissolution of an organization that fails to hold AGMs as required.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific timing requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations to hold their Annual General Meetings (AGMs) according to federal law?\n2. What are the consequences for a federally incorporated organization that fails to hold an AGM as required by federal law for two consecutive years?\n3. How do the rules for calling Annual General Meetings (AGMs) differ between federally incorporated non-profit organizations and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "049dcf38-c1ad-4ff6-9c41-4a4872d17072", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "e6d9d60346142ee413101d40b779384b6b1532f43761ee6de32d7265cae0e791", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "66bc23f6-e5cf-40ca-b991-fad90828781d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "5521570aadca5b3fb83ce9eb7314dffe5655d7c9b959ac6026be4500082fafef", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "4\nIf you are federally incorporated...  \nThe federal non-profit law\u2019s name for an AGM is the annual meeting of members. It must be called:\n\u2022 no later than fifteen months after the previous AGM; and\n\u2022 no later than six months after the end of the financial year.\nA federally incorporated organization\u2019s first AGM must be called within 18 months of being created.\nThese rules (federal law) specify when federal nonprofits have to call their AGM (i.e. give notice), unlike the \nrules for provincially incorporated non-profits, which say when you have to hold your AGM.\nAfter a federally incorporated organization fails to call an AGM as required for two years, an \u201cinterested \nperson\u201d can make an application for it to be dissolved.\nLike provincially incorporated organizations, your organization\u2019s by-laws may also further restrict the dates \nwithin which AGMs must be called. \n4. When to have a Special General Meeting (SGM)\nFor both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, the Board of Directors can call an SGM at \nany time. An", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1043, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "66bc23f6-e5cf-40ca-b991-fad90828781d": {"__data__": {"id_": "66bc23f6-e5cf-40ca-b991-fad90828781d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations regarding their Annual General Meeting (AGM) and Special General Meeting (SGM). Key topics include the timing of AGMs, the consequences of not holding AGMs as required by federal law, and the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM at any time. The section also mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates within which AGMs must be called. Key entities mentioned are federally incorporated non-profit organizations and interested persons who can apply for the dissolution of an organization that fails to hold AGMs as required.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the concept of a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains that an SGM can be called by the Board of Directors at any time for emergent issues or when the law requires a decision to be made at an SGM rather than an Annual General Meeting (AGM). It also provides information on the required proportion of votes needed for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations, such as appointing an auditor, electing directors, and ratifying amendments to by-laws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) and a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains the consequences of not holding an AGM, the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM, and the importance of addressing emergent issues or decisions that require a formal vote. Additionally, it mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates for AGMs and provides information on the required proportion of votes for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the consequences for a federally incorporated non-profit organization that fails to hold an Annual General Meeting (AGM) as required by federal law for two years?\n2. How does the ability of the Board of Directors to call a Special General Meeting (SGM) impact the decision-making process for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations?\n3. What are the specific requirements and proportions of votes needed for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations, such as appointing an auditor, electing directors, and ratifying amendments to by-laws?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "049dcf38-c1ad-4ff6-9c41-4a4872d17072", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "e6d9d60346142ee413101d40b779384b6b1532f43761ee6de32d7265cae0e791", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "1e4b0c7f-5e29-432a-8294-7f71fb03c15b", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "8e04ace92684326279e1703cadc9bbc7be51936dea7617f0b5423b64fe8ea465", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "301e9186-10a1-433b-8029-a85c42ae6f7f", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0e098b34c4e0d99518015455516d52b0a1b3354fa2bb00f3462c51a6a427c544", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "(i.e. give notice), unlike the \nrules for provincially incorporated non-profits, which say when you have to hold your AGM.\nAfter a federally incorporated organization fails to call an AGM as required for two years, an \u201cinterested \nperson\u201d can make an application for it to be dissolved.\nLike provincially incorporated organizations, your organization\u2019s by-laws may also further restrict the dates \nwithin which AGMs must be called. \n4. When to have a Special General Meeting (SGM)\nFor both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, the Board of Directors can call an SGM at \nany time. An SGM can be called whenever there is an emergent issue that is important enough that the \nmembership should have a chance to formally address it, or when the law requires that a decision be made \nat an SGM rather than an AGM.\nIf you are provincially incorporated...\nThe following table indicates the required proportion of votes in favour for various types of decisions made \nat general assemblies, and indicates those that must be made at an SGM.\nDecision (provincially", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 443, "end_char_idx": 1513, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "301e9186-10a1-433b-8029-a85c42ae6f7f": {"__data__": {"id_": "301e9186-10a1-433b-8029-a85c42ae6f7f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) and a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains the consequences of not holding an AGM, the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM, and the importance of addressing emergent issues or decisions that require a formal vote. Additionally, it mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates for AGMs and provides information on the required proportion of votes for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations.", "next_section_summary": "This section outlines the decisions that require a vote at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting, such as changing the number of directors, amending letters patent, amalgamating with another organization, creating an executive committee, or dissolving the non-profit. It also specifies that certain decisions, like transforming the non-profit into a for-profit company or removing a director before the end of their mandate, require a specific majority vote at a Special General Meeting (SGM). The section also mentions the importance of having the necessary provisions in the letters patent or by-laws to confer the power to remove a director and outlines the process for doing so. The Registraire des enterprises provides model language for letters patent related to removing a director.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the concept of a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains that an SGM can be called by the Board of Directors at any time for emergent issues or when the law requires a decision to be made at an SGM rather than an Annual General Meeting (AGM). It also provides information on the required proportion of votes needed for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations, such as appointing an auditor, electing directors, and ratifying amendments to by-laws.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific decisions that require a vote at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting, and what proportion of votes is needed for each decision?\n2. How can a Special General Meeting (SGM) be called by the Board of Directors for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, and what are the circumstances under which an SGM should be called?\n3. What are the consequences of not holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, and what role does the Board of Directors play in addressing emergent issues or decisions that require a formal vote?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "049dcf38-c1ad-4ff6-9c41-4a4872d17072", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "e6d9d60346142ee413101d40b779384b6b1532f43761ee6de32d7265cae0e791", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "66bc23f6-e5cf-40ca-b991-fad90828781d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "b41b6a8b2e4fd06908a70a194c23af415cc2d4070504e899baf7dd52cb519adf", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "a Special General Meeting (SGM)\nFor both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, the Board of Directors can call an SGM at \nany time. An SGM can be called whenever there is an emergent issue that is important enough that the \nmembership should have a chance to formally address it, or when the law requires that a decision be made \nat an SGM rather than an AGM.\nIf you are provincially incorporated...\nThe following table indicates the required proportion of votes in favour for various types of decisions made \nat general assemblies, and indicates those that must be made at an SGM.\nDecision (provincially incorporated) Where? Votes Needed\n\u2022 Appointing an auditor AGM only 50% + 1\n\u2022 Electing directors\n\u2022 Ratifying amendments to your by-laws (which must have been \nadopted in a board resolution, except some specific changes including \nones listed below that require a larger majority)\nAGM or SGM \u200250% + 1", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 892, "end_char_idx": 1812, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1d672a6c-6938-4276-9d22-5985f49dcc37": {"__data__": {"id_": "1d672a6c-6938-4276-9d22-5985f49dcc37", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "5", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the concept of a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains that an SGM can be called by the Board of Directors at any time for emergent issues or when the law requires a decision to be made at an SGM rather than an Annual General Meeting (AGM). It also provides information on the required proportion of votes needed for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations, such as appointing an auditor, electing directors, and ratifying amendments to by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of removing a director before the end of their mandate at a company's Special General Meeting (SGM) with a 4/5 majority vote. It outlines the necessary steps, including providing notice to the director and allowing them to be heard at the meeting. The section also mentions the model language provided by the Registraire des enterprises for letters patent regarding the removal of a director. Additionally, it mentions the possibility of combining an SGM and an Annual General Meeting (AGM) for efficiency.", "section_summary": "This section outlines the decisions that require a vote at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting, such as changing the number of directors, amending letters patent, amalgamating with another organization, creating an executive committee, or dissolving the non-profit. It also specifies that certain decisions, like transforming the non-profit into a for-profit company or removing a director before the end of their mandate, require a specific majority vote at a Special General Meeting (SGM). The section also mentions the importance of having the necessary provisions in the letters patent or by-laws to confer the power to remove a director and outlines the process for doing so. The Registraire des enterprises provides model language for letters patent related to removing a director.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What decisions at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting require a specific majority vote at a Special General Meeting (SGM), such as transforming the non-profit into a for-profit company or removing a director before the end of their mandate?\n2. H