ng (AGM) for organizations. It covers the election of directors, voting on resolutions/contracts, addressing funders' concerns or questions, and discussing any other business (AOB) under a \"varia\" agenda. Provincially incorporated non-profits may have the ability to authorize the chair to reorder agenda items. It is also recommended to allow discussion on topics indicated by members.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of allowing discussions on topics indicated by members during a meeting, even if it is not required by law. It also outlines the limited circumstances in which a federally incorporated non-profit can refuse to include member proposals on the agenda. Additionally, it mentions the requirement for providing written reasons for refusing a member proposal within 21 days. The section also references sample general meeting agendas and the option to forgo certain appointments as a federally incorporated non-profit if deemed a \"designated corporation.\"", "section_summary": "This section discusses addressing funders' concerns or questions, including the importance of meeting funder requirements. It also mentions the inclusion of a \"varia\" agenda item for discussing any other topics not explicitly mentioned. Additionally, it highlights the ability of provincially incorporated non-profits to authorize the chair to reorder agenda items and the importance of allowing discussions on topics indicated as important by members. The section also outlines limited circumstances in which federally incorporated non-profits can refuse to include member proposals on the agenda.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can provincially incorporated non-profits authorize the chair to reorder agenda items during a general meeting?\n2. Under what limited circumstances can federally incorporated non-profits refuse to include member proposals on the agenda?\n3. What is the importance of allowing discussions on topics indicated by members duri