d006a47eea0601573", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "37c31f2a-8862-46a3-965f-85361fd0dc37", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "8", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "9a0039b2c52ad02dc8e434d3e1e6d2a10968b3e2ba995eeacdbee36d21a83503", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "87558de9-a859-4360-a4e6-3f74d4a047a1", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "284a0afd6536990114c4f2913692eac7cba38d9b85f7645ea9e5feb074814b8c", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "the meeting.\nEven if it is not required by the law, you should consider allowing a discussion on any topic that the members \nhave indicated they feel is important. Indeed, federally incorporated non-profits can only refuse to include \nmember proposals on the agenda in limited circumstances. These include when the proposal clearly fails \nto significantly relate to your organization\u2019s activities, if its intent is clearly to settle a personal grievance, or \nwhen it wasn\u2019t submitted according to the legal requirements (e.g. it was sent outside of the proper period). \nWhenever a federally incorporated non-profit intends to refuse to a member proposal on the agenda, it must \nprovide the member with written reasons explaining why within 21 days of receiving their proposal.\nSample general meeting agendas can be found in the resources listed at the end of this info-sheet, includ-\ning in an appendix to the CSMO\u2019s Bo\u00eete \u00e0 outils, 2016.\n5 You are only allowed to forgo this appointment if, as a federally incorporated non-profit, you are what the \nlaw deems a \u201cdesignated corporation\u201d or if,", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1324, "end_char_idx": 2417, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "87558de9-a859-4360-a4e6-3f74d4a047a1": {"__data__": {"id_": "87558de9-a859-4360-a4e6-3f74d4a047a1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "8", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of allowing discussions on topics indicated by members during a meeting, even if it is not required by law. It also outlines the limited circumstances in which a federally incorporated non-profit can refuse to include member proposals on the agenda. Additionally, it mentions the requirement for providing written reasons for refusing a member proposal within 21 days. The section also references sample general meeting agendas and the option to forgo certain appointments as a federally incorporated non-profit if deemed a \"designated corporation.\"", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of giving proper notice for general meetings in provincially incorporated non-profits. It mentions that failing to give notice can invalidate a meeting, but some by-laws may have provisions for this situation. Members can renounce their right to notice, allowing a meeting to proceed without delay. The section also addresses the timeframe for giving notice, stating that if not specified in the by-laws, notice must be given ten days before the meeting.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the legal requirements for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits regarding member proposals, written reasons for refusal, general meeting agendas, designated corporations, government subsidies, and the legitimacy of decisions in the eyes of the law.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific circumstances in which a federally incorporated non-profit can refuse to include member proposals on the agenda, and what is the requirement for providing written reasons for refusal?\n2. How can a federally incorporated non-profit forgo certain appointments, and what criteria must be met to qualify as a \"designated corporation\" in this context?\n3. Is there clarity on whether decisions made by non-profits in relation to member proposals and general meeting agendas are considered legitimate in the eyes of the law, and are there any specific instances where this legitimacy may be questioned?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "c398db93-c6b8-4247-a9c3-c7431bf61392", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "8", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "96b41d6ec2e9e34c1a1c2e9ed69c15a6af0787162a0a8a8d006a47eea0601573", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "844b5beb-57ee-45bb-a5c3-4fcbd3b393b3", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "8", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "03ceb3961c94b57a78b23c82e1f40c437268bf97d83eb749bfd7f97f54e735cb", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "it was sent outside of the proper period). \nWhenever a federally incorporated non-profit intends to refuse to a member proposal on the agenda, it must \nprovide the member with written reasons explaining why within 21 days of receiving their proposal.\nSample general meeting agendas can be found in the resources listed at the end of this info-sheet, includ-\ning in an appendix to the CSMO\u2019s Bo\u00eete \u00e0 outils, 2016.\n5 You are only allowed to forgo this appointment if, as a federally incorporated non-profit, you are what the \nlaw deems a \u201cdesignated corporation\u201d or if, as a provincially incorporated non-profit, you received no more than \n$250,000 in government subsidies during the previous year.\n6 Although whether this actually legitimatizes these decisions in the eyes of the law is not clear in all instanc-\nes.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1850, "end_char_idx": 2665, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "550bf8c1-4b13-43d6-8644-0e21989f498f": {"__data__": {"id_": "550bf8c1-4b13-43d6-8644-0e21989f498f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "9", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the legal requirements for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits regarding member proposals, written reasons for refusal, general meeting agendas, designated corporations, government subsidies, and the legitimacy of decisions in the eyes of the law.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the renouncement of the right to proper notice by members at a general meeting, as well as the requirements for giving notice for provincially incorporated organizations. It outlines the timeframe for giving notice, which 