": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "17550fb51ee72450390cdcbbba568b46abc781d3d49cefb19a0f9f67de3b2b74", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "082fbdfd-fa7c-4805-9a05-5aae704d8998", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "2cf26cd1513e0b55afcb333043ef4d95ef0b0c5a90462e6e4c4138548bc53f6f", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "9\n7  Giving notice of the meeting\nYour general meeting will be at risk of being invalidated entirely unless proper notice is given. It\u2019s good prac-\ntice to regularly update your membership contact lists to be able to notify your members.\nProvincially incorporated non-profits commonly establish in their by-laws that accidentally \nfailing to give notice to a member doesn\u2019t invalidate a general meeting.\nMembers who weren\u2019t properly notified can renounce notice, and are presumed to have renounced it if they \nare present at the general meeting, unless they raise an objection. By renouncing their right to proper notice, \nmembers can allow a general meeting to be held without any delay and without the board providing any no-\ntice, for example, as long as all the members with the power to vote renounce this right. By-laws sometimes \nexplicitly state that notice can be renounced.\n7.1  If you are provincially incorporated...\nWhen must you give notice? \nIf your by-laws don\u2019t specify a timeframe, provincially incorporated organizations \nhave to give notice ten days before a", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1078, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "082fbdfd-fa7c-4805-9a05-5aae704d8998": {"__data__": {"id_": "082fbdfd-fa7c-4805-9a05-5aae704d8998", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "9", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of giving proper notice for general meetings in provincially incorporated non-profits. It mentions that failing to give notice can invalidate a meeting, but some by-laws may have provisions for this situation. Members can renounce their right to notice, allowing a meeting to proceed without delay. The section also addresses the timeframe for giving notice, stating that if not specified in the by-laws, notice must be given ten days before the meeting.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for giving notice of general meetings for provincially incorporated organizations. It outlines the timeframe for giving notice, what must be included in the notice, and how the notice must be given. Key topics include the notice timeframe, content requirements, and methods of delivery. The entities involved are provincially incorporated organizations and their members.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the renouncement of the right to proper notice by members at a general meeting, as well as the requirements for giving notice for provincially incorporated organizations. It outlines the timeframe for giving notice, which is typically ten days before a general meeting, and the information that must be included in the notice, such as the time, place, and nature of the meeting. It also mentions that by-laws can specify the notice delay and that notice can be renounced by members.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What is the timeframe for giving notice of general meetings for provincially incorporated organizations if the by-laws do not specify a timeframe?\n2. How can members renounce their right to proper notice at a general meeting, and what are the implications of doing so?\n3. What informatio