 minutes for general meetings in some of the resources listed at the end of this in -\nfo-sheet, for example in Votre association starting at page 91.\n10  Meeting Procedure\nA chairperson presides over a general meeting. Your by-laws can indicate who must serve as chair. 5 When \nchoosing the chair, consider whether the issues you will be discussing are likely to be divisive, as well as the \norganization\u2019s overarching", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 952, "end_char_idx": 2072, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9efae872-19d6-48da-b3dc-d3a3ebec9e8e": {"__data__": {"id_": "9efae872-19d6-48da-b3dc-d3a3ebec9e8e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of keeping accurate records of general meetings for both federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It highlights the need to store signed resolutions and minutes of general meetings in a secure manner. It also mentions the importance of members being able to access these records and the role of the board in granting such access. Additionally, it touches on meeting procedures, including the role of a chairperson and the importance of considering potential divisive issues when selecting a chair.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of choosing the right chair for a meeting, considering factors such as the potential divisiveness of the issues, the organization's principles, personality, and purpose. It also outlines the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization, including ensuring valid notice of the meeting and the protocol for selecting a chair if none is specified in the by-laws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses general meetings and meeting procedures for organizations. It mentions that members have the right to access meeting minutes and reports, and that the board decides on granting access. It also explains the role of a chairperson in presiding over a general meeting, and the factors to consider when choosing a chair. Additionally, it highlights the importance of ensuring valid notice of the meeting for provincially incorporated organizations.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What factors should be considered when choosing a chair for a general meeting in a provincially incorporated organization?\n2. How does the board of an organization decide on granting access to meeting minutes and reports for members who were not present at the meeting?\n3. What are the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization in ensuring valid notice of the meeting?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "cbd94be9-4790-4b77-8594-231c14b0f47d", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "0e9d329ec3823ddb199efde496a1dad47125881114c698602c7126a9efcb42aa", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "5326229c-5e0d-459e-b1a1-7cdadba0cdc5", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1dfb7eb1853ebada33de97251c70be59733f8722687a659f40dfc3dc1b7b670e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "63971b82-0332-4461-8ac2-23d995087df5", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0b714b9dd29d4b3f9c225174acff83d84377dd7ec958df1f08140325ec15d431", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "general meetings and the \nreports appended to them if they were present at the meeting. The board of such organizations decide \nwhether to grant access when other requests are made.\nYou can find sample minutes for general meetings in some of the resources listed at the end of this in -\nfo-sheet, for example in Votre association starting at page 91.\n10  Meeting Procedure\nA chairperson presides over a general meeting. Your by-laws can indicate who must serve as chair. 5 When \nchoosing the chair, consider whether the issues you will be discussing are likely to be divisive, as well as the \norganization\u2019s overarching principles, personality, and purpose. Organizations sometimes choose a chair on \nthe basis that they\u2019re a good at facilitating discussions, other times it is important for the membership to \nperceive them as neutral, and in others, it\u2019s good to have someone who is well-versed in meeting procedure.\nThe chair of a provincially incorporated organization must check that notice of the meeting was validly \ngiven.\n5 If no chair is indicated in the by-laws or the person indicated there", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1453, "end_char_idx": 2555, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "63971b82-0332-4461-8ac2-23d995087df5": {"__data__": {"id_": "63971b82-0332-4461-8ac2-23d995087df5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses general meetings and meeting procedures for organizations. It mentions that members have the right to access meeting minutes and reports, and that the board decides on granting access. It also explains the role of a chairperson in presiding over a general meeting, and the factors to consider when choosing a chair. Additionally, it highlights the importance of ensuring valid notice of the meeting for provincially incorporated organizations.", "next_section_summary": "This section covers the process of choosing a meeting secretary, checking quorum, establishing rules of procedure, voting on the adoption of the meeting agenda, and the different forms of agenda items (plenary and deliberative). It also discusses the voting procedures for provincially and federally incorporated non-profits, including the default voting procedure for federally incorporated non-profits and the option for a member to request a vote by secret ballot.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of choosing the right chair for a meeting, considering factors such as the potential divisiveness of the issues, the organization's principles, personality, and purpose. It also outlines the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization, including ensuring valid notice of the meeting and the protocol for selecting a chair if none is specified in the by-laws.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What factors should be considered when choosing a chair for a general meeting in a provincially incorporated organization?\n2. What are the responsibilities of the chair in ensuring valid notice of a meeting for a provincially incorporated organization?\n3. In the absence of a specified chair in the by-laws of a provincially incorporated organization, who is responsible for chairing the general meeting and what is the protocol for selecting a chair?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "cbd94be9-4790-4b77-8594-231c14b0f47d", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "0e9d329ec3823ddb199efde496a1dad47125881114c698602c7126a9efcb42aa", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "9efae872-19d6-48da-b3dc-d3a3ebec9e8e", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "63a200f628e78ccaecfbabdd3b2ee869445c41a95f836759678a5ee40997f237", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "5 When \nchoosing the chair, consider whether the issues you will be discussing are likely to be divisive, as well as the \norganization\u2019s overarching principles, personality, and purpose. Organizations sometimes choose a chair on \nthe basis that they\u2019re a good at facilitating discussions, other times it is important for the membership to \nperceive them as neutral, and in others, it\u2019s good to have someone who is well-versed in meeting procedure.\nThe chair of a provincially incorporated organization must check that notice of the meeting was validly \ngiven.\n5 If no chair is indicated in the by-laws or the person indicated there is absent, a provincially incorporated organi-\nzation\u2019s general meeting is chaired by its president. If the president is absent or the organization has none, then the \ntask falls to the vice-president. If none of these people are at the meeting within fifteen minutes of the start time, \nthen the members elect a chair among themselves.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1924, "end_char_idx": 2892, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "873a2a6a-8000-4603-bb04-6b4a53bc9ca1": {"__data__": {"id_": "873a2a6a-8000-4603-bb04-6b4a53bc9ca1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of choosing the right chair for a meeting, considering factors such as the potential divisiveness of the issues, the organization's principles, personality, and purpose. It also outlines the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization, including ensuring valid notice of the meeting and the protocol for selecting a chair if none is specified in the by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the voting procedures for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits during meetings. It discusses the default voting procedure for federally incorporated non-profits, which is by show of hands unless a member requests a vote by secret ballot. It also mentions that for federal non-profits, a member can request a vote by secret ballot even after a vote by show of h