ovide oth-\nerwise is to vote by show of hands, unless any member requests a vote by secret ballot. \nFor federal nonprofits, the law explicitly provides that a member can request a vote by secret ballot even \nafter the vote by show of hands has already taken place. \nFor provincially incorporated non-profits, if no voting procedure is specified by the by-laws, the chair \ndecides on the procedure. A common practice is to use the same vote by show of hands unless a member \nrequests a secret ballot, although this usually must be requested before the vote has taken place. \nAny number of possibilities, however, are possible, including", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 482, "end_char_idx": 1498, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "48903e9e-8e30-40dd-ab10-6c04419f034d": {"__data__": {"id_": "48903e9e-8e30-40dd-ab10-6c04419f034d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the voting procedures for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits during meetings. It discusses the default voting procedure for federally incorporated non-profits, which is by show of hands unless a member requests a vote by secret ballot. It also mentions that for federal non-profits, a member can request a vote by secret ballot even after a vote by show of hands has taken place. For provincially incorporated non-profits, the chair decides on the voting procedure if not specified in the by-laws, with a common practice being a vote by show of hands unless a member requests a secret ballot before the vote.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of voting during meetings, including the option of requesting a secret ballot, different methods of voting such as spoken or standing/sitting, and the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures. It also mentions that formal rules of procedure, such as Robert's Rules of Order, may not always be necessary for small non-profits, and suggests considering a simplified set of rules.", "section_summary": "The key topics of the section include voting procedures for nonprofit organizations, specifically regarding the use of show of hands and secret ballots. It also discusses the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures, such as not requiring motions to be seconded. The entities mentioned are federal and provincially incorporated nonprofits, as well as members and chairs involved in the voting process.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How do federal and provincially incorporated non-profits typically handle voting procedures during meetings?\n2. What options do members of federal non-profits have for requesting a vote by secret ballot, even after a show of hands has taken place?\n3. In what ways can organizations adapt or create their own meeting procedures, and what are some examples of alternative voting methods mentioned in the document?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "a4ba6f22-7643-483b-bb82-856847715c65", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "4bca591593ae6c11ac6b3070148b84e2325a38fc8ba855c5f79b1ac71d5dc075", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "3bc55f24-cd7d-4028-81cf-632e4d265f00", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "77633bba9e57e4d1549b5458c78a2992276c60a80a05da5df25b96266148c14c", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "0460fb5f-798d-4d58-9878-52f0da01c66e", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "c9206033298399e318a776558d71d01bade8ce43955365b7599181ddc3a76c38", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "is to vote by show of hands, unless any member requests a vote by secret ballot. \nFor federal nonprofits, the law explicitly provides that a member can request a vote by secret ballot even \nafter the vote by show of hands has already taken place. \nFor provincially incorporated non-profits, if no voting procedure is specified by the by-laws, the chair \ndecides on the procedure. A common practice is to use the same vote by show of hands unless a member \nrequests a secret ballot, although this usually must be requested before the vote has taken place. \nAny number of possibilities, however, are possible, including a vote by spoken \u201cyay\u201d or \u201cnay\u201d, by people stand-\ning (to indicate a vote in favour) or sitting (to oppose), or any of an endless array of other methods are also \npossible to adopt.\n!\nMeeting procedure does not have to be overly formal and organizations can \nadapt or completely build their own rules. For example, there is no need to require \nthat motions must be \u201cseconded\u201d. Although the most well-known rules of pro", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 881, "end_char_idx": 1917, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0460fb5f-798d-4d58-9878-52f0da01c66e": {"__data__": {"id_": "0460fb5f-798d-4d58-9878-52f0da01c66e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of the section include voting procedures for nonprofit organizations, specifically regarding the use of show of hands and secret ballots. It also discusses the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures, such as not requiring motions to be seconded. The entities mentioned are federal and provincially incorporated nonprofits, as well as members and chairs involved in the voting process.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the voting procedures for provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to hold director elections by mail and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent. It also mentions the power of the meeting chair to propose motions, vote on motions, and cast a deciding vote in case of a tie. Additionally, it highlights the flexibility in voting for federally incorporated non-profits, allowing for voting by members who are not physically present through technological or electronic means.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the process of voting during meetings, including the option of requesting a secret ballot, different methods of voting such as spoken or standing/sitting, and the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures. It also mentions that formal rules of procedure, such as Robert's Rules of Order, may not always be necessary for small non-profits, and suggests considering a simplified set of rules.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can nonprofit organizations adapt or create their own meeting procedures, such as not requiring motions to be seconded?\n2. What are the different methods of voting mentioned in the document, such as spoken \"yay\" or \"nay\", standing or sitting, and requesting a secret ballot?\n3. In what situations may formal rules of procedure, like Robert's Rules of Order, not be necessary for small non-profits, and what alternative options are suggested for creating a simplified set of rules for meetings?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "a4ba6f22-7643-483b-bb82-856847715c65", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "4bca591593ae6c11ac6b3070148b84e2325a38fc8ba855c5f79b1ac71d5dc075", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "48903e9e-8e30-40dd-ab10-6c04419f034d", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "321b61d32f6e3992f0123be5ca48c1ca6fe8f7e14a980e2161ea41778d33c3ec", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "member \nrequests a secret ballot, although this usually must be requested before the vote has taken place. \nAny number of possibilities, however, are possible, including a vote by spoken \u201cyay\u201d or \u201cnay\u201d, by people stand-\ning (to indicate a vote in favour) or sitting (to oppose), or any of an endless array of other methods are also \npossible to adopt.\n!\nMeeting procedure does not have to be overly formal and organizations can \nadapt or completely build their own rules. For example, there is no need to require \nthat motions must be \u201cseconded\u201d. Although the most well-known rules of pro -\ncedure (Robert\u2019s Rules of Order, the Code Morin , etc.) are widely used, they may \noften be more cumbersome than necessary for the purposes a small non-profit. \nIt\u2019s up to you to decide whether a simplified set of rules is more appropriate.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1329, "end_char_idx": 2160, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6e104a0e-1d75-476c-b1f5-69c9a2360968": {"__data__": {"id_": "6e104a0e-1d75-476c-b1f5-69c9a2360968", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of voting during meetings, including the option of requesting a secret ballot, different methods of voting such as spoken or standing/sitting, and the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures. It also mentions that formal rules of procedure, such as Robert's Rules of Order, may not always be necessary for small non-profits, and suggests considering a simplified set of rules.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting procedures for members of non-profit organizations, including the power of the chair to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie, the ability to adopt resolutions with unanimous consent, and the flexibility in voting methods for federally incorporated non-profits. The entities mentioned are members, chairs, and Corporations Canada.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the voting procedures for provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to hold director elections by mail and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent. It also mentions the power of the meeting chair to propose motions, vote on motions, and cast a deciding vote in case of a tie. Additionally, it highlights the flexibility in voting for federally incorporated non-profits, allowing for voting by members who are not physically present through technological or electronic means.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can provincially incorporated non-profits hold director elections and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent?\n2. What voting rights and powers does the meeting chair have in provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie?\n3. In what ways do federally incorporated non-profits offer more flexibility in voting for members who are not physically present, such as through technological or electronic means?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "6a71c415-c6a3-411c-b9fb-7aa375a08428", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "f35a1be5a52e904855d62af47ebd5a305f80e3b59e37e14f996007723af00642", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "14\nPROVINCIALL Y INCORPORATED NON-PROFITS...  \nProvincially incorporated non-profits can hold the election of their directors by mail, though this \nmethod is probably invalid to use for adopting general meeting resolutions, if their by-laws provide for this \n(writes Paul Martel). \nFor provincially incorporated organizations, the meeting chair not only has the right to propose \nmotions and vote on all motions in their capacity as a member, but also has the power, in the case of a tie, \nto cast a second, deciding vote, unless that power is withdrawn by the letters patent or by-laws. \nProvincially incorporated non-profits can also adopt resolutions with unanimous consent if no one \nasks for a vote, and the chair can declare the resolution to have unanimously passed. However, any mem-\nber, including the chair, can ask for a vote.\nFederally incorporated non-profits allow more flexibility in voting by members who are not \nphysically present. A vote can be held entirely by telephone or any other technological or electronic", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1031, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6a71c415-c6a3-411c-b9fb-7aa375a08428": {"__data__": {"id_": "6a71c415-c6a3-411c-b9fb-7aa375a08428", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the voting procedures for provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to hold director elections by mail and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent. It also mentions the power of the meeting chair to propose motions, vote on motions, and cast a deciding vote in case of a tie. Additionally, it highlights the flexibility in voting for federally incorporated non-profits, allowing for voting by members who are not physically present through technological or electronic means.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the flexibility in voting methods for members who are not physically present in non-profit organizations. It mentions the use of telephone or electronic communication for voting, as well as the possibility of absentee voting by proxy, mail, or electronic means with certain conditions. It also explains the voting requirements for decisions, including simple majority and supermajority, and how they are counted in the absence of quorum or for provincially incorporated non-profits.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting procedures for members of non-profit organizations, including the power of the chair to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie, the ability to adopt resolutions with unanimous consent, and the flexibility in voting methods for federally incorporated non-profits. The entities mentioned are members, chairs, and Corporations Canada.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can provincially incorporated non-profits adopt resolutions with unanimous consent, and what role does the chair play in this process?\n2. What voting methods are available for members who are not physically present in federally incorporated non-profits, and what conditions must be met for absentee voting by proxy, mail, or electronic means?\n3. What decisions require a simple majority vote to pass in non-profit organizations, and how are these votes counted in the absence of quorum or for provincially incorporated non-profits?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "6e104a0e-1d75-476c-b1f5-69c9a2360968", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "058085856cb2e10c69ab11e5aba617248c276167cfa065a6f4ed6c2f2d42072c", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "5d96a1e5-d631-4c1a-9f80-bb065c175f50", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "15b40cf66fd739f82ad93a3798649e6bbbb38896d369dd2b587ae14caf5f2a0a", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "a member, but also has the power, in the case of a tie, \nto cast a second, deciding vote, unless that power is withdrawn by the letters patent or by-laws. \nProvincially incorporated non-profits can also adopt resolutions with unanimous consent if no one \nasks for a vote, and the chair can declare the resolution to have unanimously passed. However, any mem-\nber, including the chair, can ask for a vote.\nFederally incorporated non-profits allow more flexibility in voting by members who are not \nphysically present. A vote can be held entirely by telephone or any other technological or electronic commu-\nnications method the organization deploys, unless the by-laws provide otherwise. It is also possible for the \nby-laws to authorize absentee voting by proxy, by mail, or by electronic means, so long as certain conditions \nin the law are met. You can also ask for special permission from Corporations Canada to be authorized to \nuse another absentee voting method.\nDecisions that require 50%+1 votes to pass are usually counted using a simple majority", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 433, "end_char_idx": 1488, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5d96a1e5-d631-4c1a-9f80-bb065c175f50": {"__data__": {"id_": "5d96a1e5-d631-4c1a-9f80-bb065c175f50", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting procedures for members of non-profit organizations, including the power of the chair to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie, the ability to adopt resolutions with unanimous consent, and the flexibility in voting methods for federally incorporated non-profits. The entities mentioned are members, chairs, and Corporations Canada.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting methods and requirements for decision-making in non-profit organizations. It discusses the use of simple majority votes, absolute majority counts, and supermajorities. It also mentions the importance of considering different classes of members and the potential impact of abstentions on voting outcomes. The section emphasizes the need for organizations to consult additional resources for a more comprehensive understanding of voting processes, especially in cases where different classes of members are involved.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the flexibility in voting methods for members who are not physically present in non-profit organizations. It mentions the use of telephone or electronic communication for voting, as well as the possibility of absentee voting by proxy, mail, or electronic means with certain conditions. It also explains the voting requirements for decisions, including simple majority and supermajority, and how they are counted in the absence of quorum or for provincially incorporated non-profits.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can non-profit organizations allow members who are not physically present to participate in voting processes?\n2. What are the conditions that must be met for absentee voting by proxy, mail, or electronic means to be authorized in non-profit organizations?\n3. In the absence of quorum for provincially incorporated non-profits, how are decisions that require a simple majority of votes cast by members present counted, and how do abstentions and absences factor into the count?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "6a71c415-c6a3-411c-b9fb-7aa375a08428", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "17ef4be0e4b238d4b0c9b8cd1fc65912683c558fbef1f2205dcea1418f097012", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "0446c746-0a39-4bc5-b2b5-91b17dcebbf7", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "829e61e98aebd257ec18e3d30e7043f5452a7e4ec905cb318ccd146b9696b22e", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "allow more flexibility in voting by members who are not \nphysically present. A vote can be held entirely by telephone or any other technological or electronic commu-\nnications method the organization deploys, unless the by-laws provide otherwise. It is also possible for the \nby-laws to authorize absentee voting by proxy, by mail, or by electronic means, so long as certain conditions \nin the law are met. You can also ask for special permission from Corporations Canada to be authorized to \nuse another absentee voting method.\nDecisions that require 50%+1 votes to pass are usually counted using a simple majority of votes cast by \nthe members present forming quorum. Exceptionally, though, when no quorum is specified in the by-laws \nof a provincially incorporated non-profit, the count is an absolute majority, and abstentions and absences \nare also counted.\nWhen supermajorities are required for provincially incorporated non-profits (e.g. 2/3 majorities), the \ntotal is calculated with respect to all members present, and so abstentions have the same effect", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 873, "end_char_idx": 1936, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0446c746-0a39-4bc5-b2b5-91b17dcebbf7": {"__data__": {"id_": "0446c746-0a39-4bc5-b2b5-91b17dcebbf7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the flexibility in voting methods for members who are not physically present in non-profit organizations. It mentions the use of telephone or electronic communication for voting, as well as the possibility of absentee voting by proxy, mail, or electronic means with certain conditions. It also explains the voting requirements for decisions, including simple majority and supermajority, and how they are counted in the absence of quorum or for provincially incorporated non-profits.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the calculation of votes in organizations, including the impact of abstentions and the importance of considering different classes of members. It also mentions the validity of written resolutions for federally incorporated non-profits versus provincially incorporated ones. Additionally, it highlights the ability of by-laws to adjust voting requirements and the possibility of making decisions by consensus in federal non-profits.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting methods and requirements for decision-making in non-profit organizations. It discusses the use of simple majority votes, absolute majority counts, and supermajorities. It also mentions the importance of considering different classes of members and the potential impact of abstentions on voting outcomes. The section emphasizes the need for organizations to consult additional resources for a more comprehensive understanding of voting processes, especially in cases where different classes of members are involved.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How are votes calculated in provincially incorporated non-profits when no quorum is specified in the by-laws?\n2. What is the impact of abstentions on voting outcomes in provincially incorporated non-profits requiring supermajorities?\n3. How does the presence of different classes of members in an organization affect the voting process, especially in cases where even \"non-voting\" members must be given a say?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "5d96a1e5-d631-4c1a-9f80-bb065c175f50", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "47a499f993694ff09ee3f839eae7ca732810932517a96f7dbebe5f521ace6815", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "3660c50d-f632-4e87-accd-6ff1258fcc46", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "1ee150d3913135365ae1acf502cd69ac6f5e8b96266bea64dfd1cdb53cf898aa", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "be authorized to \nuse another absentee voting method.\nDecisions that require 50%+1 votes to pass are usually counted using a simple majority of votes cast by \nthe members present forming quorum. Exceptionally, though, when no quorum is specified in the by-laws \nof a provincially incorporated non-profit, the count is an absolute majority, and abstentions and absences \nare also counted.\nWhen supermajorities are required for provincially incorporated non-profits (e.g. 2/3 majorities), the \ntotal is calculated with respect to all members present, and so abstentions have the same effect as a vote \nagainst.\nIf your organization has created different classes of members, you should be sure not to rely solely on the \nsimplified information above, and should look to other resources, since the process is more complicated: \nin a number of situations even members designated as \u201cnon-voting\u201d must be given a say!\nAlthough a written resolution signed by all of the members of a federally incorporated \nnon-profit can be just as valid as one passed at a general meeting held", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1348, "end_char_idx": 2418, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3660c50d-f632-4e87-accd-6ff1258fcc46": {"__data__": {"id_": "3660c50d-f632-4e87-accd-6ff1258fcc46", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting methods and requirements for decision-making in non-profit organizations. It discusses the use of simple majority votes, absolute majority counts, and supermajorities. It also mentions the importance of considering different classes of members and the potential impact of abstentions on voting outcomes. The section emphasizes the need for organizations to consult additional resources for a more comprehensive understanding of voting processes, especially in cases where different classes of members are involved.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the validity of written resolutions in federally incorporated non-profits, the limitations on passing resolutions in provincially incorporated non-profits, the ability to adjust voting requirements in by-laws, and the option for federal non-profits to make decisions by consensus. The section also mentions the importance of defining consensus, verifying its attainment, and providing a process for voting on issues where consensus cannot be reached. The entities involved in this section are federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the calculation of votes in organizations, including the impact of abstentions and the importance of considering different classes of members. It also mentions the validity of written resolutions for federally incorporated non-profits versus provincially incorporated ones. Additionally, it highlights the ability of by-laws to adjust voting requirements and the possibility of making decisions by consensus in federal non-profits.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How do abstentions impact the calculation of votes in organizations, particularly when different classes of members are involved?\n2. What are the differences in the validity of written resolutions between federally incorporated non-profits and provincially incorporated non-profits?\n3. How can by-laws be used to adjust voting requirements in organizations, and what options do federal non-profits have for making decisions by consensus?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "0446c746-0a39-4bc5-b2b5-91b17dcebbf7", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "bb3be2b9cc1cd57ed39345faa27c1d82d9fc6fa3e50b8aadc44b4e2c472ce1f3", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "fee81634-74cb-4104-9582-ef8dd5c97a70", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "5bf5c1b18340cd77933a8fe7e0994aa2aa677f365f9ad75bcb8c478413f6825f", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "(e.g. 2/3 majorities), the \ntotal is calculated with respect to all members present, and so abstentions have the same effect as a vote \nagainst.\nIf your organization has created different classes of members, you should be sure not to rely solely on the \nsimplified information above, and should look to other resources, since the process is more complicated: \nin a number of situations even members designated as \u201cnon-voting\u201d must be given a say!\nAlthough a written resolution signed by all of the members of a federally incorporated \nnon-profit can be just as valid as one passed at a general meeting held in person, provincial-\nly incorporated non-profits cannot validly pass resolutions of the membership this way.\nYour by-laws can raise the proportion of votes required for many de -\ncisions, and federal non-profits can even make many of their deci -\nsions by consensus, so long as their by-laws define the meaning \nof consensus, the way to verify that it was obtained, and the way to \nsubmit to a vote any issue on which consensus cannot be", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1812, "end_char_idx": 2858, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fee81634-74cb-4104-9582-ef8dd5c97a70": {"__data__": {"id_": "fee81634-74cb-4104-9582-ef8dd5c97a70", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the calculation of votes in organizations, including the impact of abstentions and the importance of considering different classes of members. It also mentions the validity of written resolutions for federally incorporated non-profits versus provincially incorporated ones. Additionally, it highlights the ability of by-laws to adjust voting requirements and the possibility of making decisions by consensus in federal non-profits.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the different levels of accounting analysis that can be applied to financial statements: compilation, financial review, and audit. It also mentions the minimum levels of analysis required by law and the possibility of needing a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements. Additionally, it highlights the requirement for provincially incorporated organizations to present a balance sheet at their AGM, with the period covered ending no more than four months before the meeting.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the validity of written resolutions in federally incorporated non-profits, the limitations on passing resolutions in provincially incorporated non-profits, the ability to adjust voting requirements in by-laws, and the option for federal non-profits to make decisions by consensus. The section also mentions the importance of defining consensus, verifying its attainment, and providing a process for voting on issues where consensus cannot be reached. The entities involved in this section are federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can federally incorporated non-profits pass resolutions without holding a general meeting in person?\n2. What role do by-laws play in adjusting voting requirements for non-profit organizations?\n3. What are the specific requirements for federal non-profits to make decisions by consensus, as outlined in their by-laws?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "1d441bbf722d9c03208ce217cba5ddcf9159c5b131d6b8016b487985e18bce12", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "3660c50d-f632-4e87-accd-6ff1258fcc46", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "76307a2ca45c67049a772e6db61e5dd5a28c5cb538300e62c46654d8f1680113", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "a written resolution signed by all of the members of a federally incorporated \nnon-profit can be just as valid as one passed at a general meeting held in person, provincial-\nly incorporated non-profits cannot validly pass resolutions of the membership this way.\nYour by-laws can raise the proportion of votes required for many de -\ncisions, and federal non-profits can even make many of their deci -\nsions by consensus, so long as their by-laws define the meaning \nof consensus, the way to verify that it was obtained, and the way to \nsubmit to a vote any issue on which consensus cannot be reached.?", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 2268, "end_char_idx": 2868, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7bebe7da-55c3-4d02-ab55-512d89eafa08": {"__data__": {"id_": "7bebe7da-55c3-4d02-ab55-512d89eafa08", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the validity of written resolutions in federally incorporated non-profits, the limitations on passing resolutions in provincially incorporated non-profits, the ability to adjust voting requirements in by-laws, and the option for federal non-profits to make decisions by consensus. The section also mentions the importance of defining consensus, verifying its attainment, and providing a process for voting on issues where consensus cannot be reached. The entities involved in this section are federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the accounting procedures and financial statement requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It emphasizes the importance of accurate financial statements and mentions that the law sets minimum levels of analysis, but organizations may have additional requirements in their by-laws or from funders. The financial statements required for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) include a balance sheet and may also include a general statement of income and expenditure. Provincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their constitution.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the different levels of accounting analysis that can be applied to financial statements: compilation, financial review, and audit. It also mentions the minimum levels of analysis required by law and the possibility of needing a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements. Additionally, it highlights the requirement for provincially incorporated organizations to present a balance sheet at their AGM, with the period covered ending no more than four months before the meeting.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the three levels of accounting analysis that financial statements can be subjected to, and how do they differ in terms of rigor and assurance of accuracy?\n2. What are the minimum levels of analysis required by law for financial statements, and what factors may require a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements?\n3. For provincially incorporated non-profit organizations, what financial statements are required to be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM), and what is the timeframe for the information covered in the balance sheet?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "768dc53f-9953-42ac-9ac8-20cfbce559d1", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "08208c526c41499bc084d6d2726f58fbd710f485818dd24b7478b7df263b4c82", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "842bd02e-bc0c-4bb0-a6c6-0179ee07d3e3", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "bdb9b4aeccc5808a876fd6d9008b6580e710f008c3d39649eb31ec8f3d363614", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "15\n11  Presenting financial statements\nYour financial statements can be subjected to one of three levels of accounting analysis:\n\u2022  a compilation, or notice to reader is the least onerous option, and is largely a literal compila-\ntion    of the relevant information;\n\u2022 a financial review or review engagement involves analysis of the information, including basic\n checks to ensure that the numbers are reasonable and internally consistent; and\n\u2022 an audit is the most rigorous accounting procedure, and provides the strongest assurance that the \n financial statements are accurate.\nThe law requires certain minimum levels of analysis in different situations, but you may also be required to \nexercise a more rigorous level of analysis by the rules in your by-laws, your letters patent, or requirements \nmade of you by your funders.\nIF YOU ARE PROVINCIALL Y INCORPORATED  \nThe financial statements that you must present at your AGM always include a balance sheet (which, as men-\ntioned before, must cover a period ending no more than four months before the AGM 5).\nProvincially incorporated", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1088, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "842bd02e-bc0c-4bb0-a6c6-0179ee07d3e3": {"__data__": {"id_": "842bd02e-bc0c-4bb0-a6c6-0179ee07d3e3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the different levels of accounting analysis that can be applied to financial statements: compilation, financial review, and audit. It also mentions the minimum levels of analysis required by law and the possibility of needing a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements. Additionally, it highlights the requirement for provincially incorporated organizations to present a balance sheet at their AGM, with the period covered ending no more than four months before the meeting.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the financial reporting requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their Annual General Meeting (AGM). It mentions the need for a balance sheet covering a period ending no more than four months before the AGM, as well as a general statement of income and expenditure. The financial information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws must be presented. If an auditor was appointed, their report must also be attached and presented at the AGM.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the accounting procedures and financial statement requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It emphasizes the importance of accurate financial statements and mentions that the law sets minimum levels of analysis, but organizations may have additional requirements in their by-laws or from funders. The financial statements required for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) include a balance sheet and may also include a general statement of income and expenditure. Provincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their constitution.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific financial reporting requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. What are the minimum levels of analysis required by law for financial statements of non-profit organizations, and what additional requirements may organizations have based on their by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements?\n3. How can provincially incorporated non-profit organizations enhance their financial statements for the AGM by including a general statement of income and expenditure, and what resources can they refer to for guidance on preparing such statements?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "768dc53f-9953-42ac-9ac8-20cfbce559d1", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "08208c526c41499bc084d6d2726f58fbd710f485818dd24b7478b7df263b4c82", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "7bebe7da-55c3-4d02-ab55-512d89eafa08", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "f27b36f83214076d878297b93f771684a0958cc5f03161ba7a8832c8d25fdda1", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "22a929c5-011e-49b2-99b9-ed030773cf2a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "0a98e73c7de021ceb81732c6f41ea0a1d491a7b8c7412a96323f80efebbc1e60", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "accounting procedure, and provides the strongest assurance that the \n financial statements are accurate.\nThe law requires certain minimum levels of analysis in different situations, but you may also be required to \nexercise a more rigorous level of analysis by the rules in your by-laws, your letters patent, or requirements \nmade of you by your funders.\nIF YOU ARE PROVINCIALL Y INCORPORATED  \nThe financial statements that you must present at your AGM always include a balance sheet (which, as men-\ntioned before, must cover a period ending no more than four months before the AGM 5).\nProvincially incorporated non-profits can  add to their financial statements a general statement of income \nand expenditure for the financial period ending nearest to the date of their balance sheet. The CSMO\u2019s Bo\u00eete \n\u00e0 outils, 2016 (referenced at the end of this info-sheet), provides at page 70 a sample of a statement of \nincome and expenditure.\nProvincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their consti-\ntution or", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 476, "end_char_idx": 1531, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "22a929c5-011e-49b2-99b9-ed030773cf2a": {"__data__": {"id_": "22a929c5-011e-49b2-99b9-ed030773cf2a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the accounting procedures and financial statement requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It emphasizes the importance of accurate financial statements and mentions that the law sets minimum levels of analysis, but organizations may have additional requirements in their by-laws or from funders. The financial statements required for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) include a balance sheet and may also include a general statement of income and expenditure. Provincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their constitution.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the presentation of a statement of income and expenditure, financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws, approval by the current board, and the attachment and presentation of an auditor's report if applicable. The section also mentions the possibility of extending the deadline for submitting financial information to six months for organizations based outside of Quebec. Key entities involved are provincially incorporated organizations, the current board of directors, and auditors.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the financial reporting requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their Annual General Meeting (AGM). It mentions the need for a balance sheet covering a period ending no more than four months before the AGM, as well as a general statement of income and expenditure. The financial information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws must be presented. If an auditor was appointed, their report must also be attached and presented at the AGM.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific financial reporting requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. How can provincially incorporated non-profits add a general statement of income and expenditure to their financial statements?\n3. What steps must be taken by provincially incorporated organizations in terms of financial information approval and presentation at the AGM, including the role of auditors?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "768dc53f-9953-42ac-9ac8-20cfbce559d1", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "08208c526c41499bc084d6d2726f58fbd710f485818dd24b7478b7df263b4c82", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "842bd02e-bc0c-4bb0-a6c6-0179ee07d3e3", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "b0cc326997fc563c88334f827d174797de6a0c9d0644c74771b11de599c946c4", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "1e0a8995-6dde-453a-93ca-61778f126a5e", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "fca21f514977cd150201a326fcd1c41da1a39915dc964b15dc0936ababd52212", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "balance sheet (which, as men-\ntioned before, must cover a period ending no more than four months before the AGM 5).\nProvincially incorporated non-profits can  add to their financial statements a general statement of income \nand expenditure for the financial period ending nearest to the date of their balance sheet. The CSMO\u2019s Bo\u00eete \n\u00e0 outils, 2016 (referenced at the end of this info-sheet), provides at page 70 a sample of a statement of \nincome and expenditure.\nProvincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their consti-\ntution or by-laws. \nAll of this information must have been approved by the current board before being submitted to the AGM. \nA director should sign them as evidence of this.\nFinally, if your organization named an auditor, their report must also be attached and presented, though they \ndo not necessarily need to present their report in person. \n5 If the organization\u2019s work is based outside of Quebec, however, it can adopt a resolution at a general meeting \nto extend this to", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 947, "end_char_idx": 1998, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1e0a8995-6dde-453a-93ca-61778f126a5e": {"__data__": {"id_": "1e0a8995-6dde-453a-93ca-61778f126a5e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the financial reporting requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their Annual General Meeting (AGM). It mentions the need for a balance sheet covering a period ending no more than four months before the AGM, as well as a general statement of income and expenditure. The financial information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws must be presented. If an auditor was appointed, their report must also be attached and presented at the AGM.", "next_section_summary": "This section provides information for federally incorporated non-profits on the financial statements that must be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM). The required financial statements include a balance sheet, statements of comprehensive income or retained earnings, changes in equity or income, and cash flows or changes in financial position. These statements must be comparative, covering the previous two financial years. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution, by-laws, and member agreements must be presented. The financial statements must conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada. Approval by the current board and signature by a director are required before submission to the AGM. If a public accountant was named by the organization, their report must also be included.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the presentation of a statement of income and expenditure, financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws, approval by the current board, and the attachment and presentation of an auditor's report if applicable. The section also mentions the possibility of extending the deadline for submitting financial information to six months for organizations based outside of Quebec. Key entities involved are provincially incorporated organizations, the current board of directors, and auditors.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What financial statements are required to be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM) for federally incorporated non-profit organizations, according to the information provided in this section?\n2. How can organizations based outside of Quebec extend the deadline for submitting financial information to the AGM, as mentioned in the excerpt?\n3. What are the specific requirements for the approval and submission of financial information by provincially incorporated non-profit organizations at their AGM, as outlined in the section summary?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "768dc53f-9953-42ac-9ac8-20cfbce559d1", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "08208c526c41499bc084d6d2726f58fbd710f485818dd24b7478b7df263b4c82", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "22a929c5-011e-49b2-99b9-ed030773cf2a", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "fa018c62ad266300372f0b190c0af552eb8a0491794cfe71690300e233f17963", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "a sample of a statement of \nincome and expenditure.\nProvincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their consti-\ntution or by-laws. \nAll of this information must have been approved by the current board before being submitted to the AGM. \nA director should sign them as evidence of this.\nFinally, if your organization named an auditor, their report must also be attached and presented, though they \ndo not necessarily need to present their report in person. \n5 If the organization\u2019s work is based outside of Quebec, however, it can adopt a resolution at a general meeting \nto extend this to six months.", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 1360, "end_char_idx": 2010, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "38458d4b-1110-4e8f-9dff-4484a143463a": {"__data__": {"id_": "38458d4b-1110-4e8f-9dff-4484a143463a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "16", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the presentation of a statement of income and expenditure, financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws, approval by the current board, and the attachment and presentation of an auditor's report if applicable. The section also mentions the possibility of extending the deadline for submitting financial information to six months for organizations based outside of Quebec. Key entities involved are provincially incorporated organizations, the current board of directors, and auditors.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the requirements for federally incorporated non-profits to submit comparative financial statements that conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by CPA Canada. The information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director before being submitted to the AGM. If the organization has named a public accountant, their report must also be attached and presented. Failure to comply with these requirements is considered an offence. Additionally, there are additional obligations related to financial statements for non-profit subsidiaries.", "section_summary": "This section provides information for federally incorporated non-profits on the financial statements that must be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM). The required financial statements include a balance sheet, statements of comprehensive income or retained earnings, changes in equity or income, and cash flows or changes in financial position. These statements must be comparative, covering the previous two financial years. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution, by-laws, and member agreements must be presented. The financial statements must conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada. Approval by the current board and signature by a director are required before submission to the AGM. If a public accountant was named by the organization, their report must also be included.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific financial statements that federally incorporated non-profits must present at their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. What are the requirements for the approval and submission of financial information by federally incorporated non-profits, as outlined in the document?\n3. How does the document specify the role of Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada in establishing generally accepted accounting principles for federally incorporated non-profits?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "3b056607-e0c2-4906-8634-a50be5a38bc0", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "16", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "48fc08e90168d1ab4fcef74ba397cfb15c02551bfa04b419e9983f40863bd109", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "b18a487e-2d70-40a4-94a5-8c176283b5b2", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "b66729446aceabb49f416c04b0537e78882faaa0d4c64f2dc452b352ef56eec5", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "16\nIF YOU ARE FEDERALL Y INCORPORATED\nThe financial statements that you must present at your AGM include a balance sheet, and statements:\n\u2022 of comprehensive income or of retained earnings;\n\u2022 of changes in equity or of income; and\n\u2022 of cash flows or of changes in financial position.\nThese generally must be comparative financial statements, relating to the previous two financial years. \nYou must also present any financial information required by your constitution, your by-laws and any unani-\nmous member agreement. \nThe law regulating federally incorporated non-profits is explicit that its comparative financial statements \nmust conform to \u201cgenerally accepted accounting principles\u201d, as established by Chartered Professional Ac-\ncountants (CPA) Canada. For more on this topic, see Coco\u2019s info-sheet on Generally Accepted Accounting \nPrinciples for Small Non-Profits. \nAll of this information must have been approved by the current board before being submitted to the AGM. \nA director should sign them as evidence of this. Finally, if your organization named a public accountant, \ntheir report must also be", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1109, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b18a487e-2d70-40a4-94a5-8c176283b5b2": {"__data__": {"id_": "b18a487e-2d70-40a4-94a5-8c176283b5b2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "16", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section provides information for federally incorporated non-profits on the financial statements that must be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM). The required financial statements include a balance sheet, statements of comprehensive income or retained earnings, changes in equity or income, and cash flows or changes in financial position. These statements must be comparative, covering the previous two financial years. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution, by-laws, and member agreements must be presented. The financial statements must conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada. Approval by the current board and signature by a director are required before submission to the AGM. If a public accountant was named by the organization, their report must also be included.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the obligations and requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations related to financial statements at their Annual General Meetings (AGMs). Key topics include the signing of financial statements by directors, the attachment and presentation of a public accountant's report, and the dissemination of financial information to members. It is emphasized that it is an offence to publish or disseminate financial statements that are not approved and signed, or not accompanied by the public accountant's report. Additionally, there are specific obligations for federally incorporated non-profits with subsidiaries. The section also mentions the option of providing a summary of financial documents to members, with instructions on how to obtain a full copy at no cost.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the requirements for federally incorporated non-profits to submit comparative financial statements that conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by CPA Canada. The information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director before being submitted to the AGM. If the organization has named a public accountant, their report must also be attached and presented. Failure to comply with these requirements is considered an offence. Additionally, there are additional obligations related to financial statements for non-profit subsidiaries.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific financial statements that federally incorporated non-profits are required to present at their Annual General Meetings (AGMs), and what are the key requirements for these statements to comply with generally accepted accounting principles established by CPA Canada?\n2. What are the consequences for a federally incorporated non-profit if they fail to have their financial statements approved, signed by a director, and accompanied by a public accountant's report before publication or dissemination?\n3. What additional obligations and requirements do federally incorporated non-profits with subsidiaries have in relation to their financial stateme