he current board before being submitted to the AGM. \nA director should sign them as evidence of this. Finally, if your organization named a public accountant, \ntheir report must also be attached and presented, though they do not in all cases need to present their \nreport personally.\nIf you are federally incorporated non-profit also has subsidiaries, there are additional obligations related to \ntheir financial statements.\n!\nIt is an offence for a federally incorporated non-profit to publish or dissemi -\nnate these financial statements if they are not approved and signed, or if they \nare not accompanied by the public accountant\u2019s report, if one was produced. \nCertain particularities apply to the presentation", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 480, "end_char_idx": 1639, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4ec2240c-2233-4d62-80f4-c70fc23787b2": {"__data__": {"id_": "4ec2240c-2233-4d62-80f4-c70fc23787b2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "16", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the requirements for federally incorporated non-profits to submit comparative financial statements that conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by CPA Canada. The information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director before being submitted to the AGM. If the organization has named a public accountant, their report must also be attached and presented. Failure to comply with these requirements is considered an offence. Additionally, there are additional obligations related to financial statements for non-profit subsidiaries.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for presenting financial information at annual general meetings (AGMs) for federally incorporated organizations. It mentions that financial statements must be approved and signed, and if applicable, accompanied by a public accountant's report. It also outlines specific requirements for federally incorporated non-profits, such as sending members copies or summaries of financial documents and providing access to full copies at no cost. Additionally, it suggests ways to streamline this process, such as notifying members that documents are available at the organization's head office for free.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the obligations and requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations related to financial statements at their Annual General Meetings (AGMs). Key topics include the signing of financial statements by directors, the attachment and presentation of a public accountant's report, and the dissemination of financial information to members. It is emphasized that it is an offence to publish or disseminate financial statements that are not approved and signed, or not accompanied by the public accountant's report. Additionally, there are specific obligations for federally incorporated non-profits with subsidiaries. The section also mentions the option of providing a summary of financial documents to members, with instructions on how to obtain a full copy at no cost.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific obligations for federally incorporated non-profit organizations with subsidiaries in relation to their financial statements at Annual General Meetings (AGMs)?\n2. How can federally incorporated non-profits streamline the process of providing financial information to their members, as suggested in the section summary?\n3. What are the consequences for federally incorporated non-profits if they fail to comply with the requirements for submittin