ta_separator": "\n", "text": "18\nEligibility. The law requires directors to be at least 18 years old; to not currently be bankrupt; to not \nhave certain intellectual disabilities, notably when they have been \u201cdeclared incapable by a court\u201d; and to \nbe a \u201cnatural person\u201d (in other words, they can\u2019t be an incorporated organization, which the law also consid-\ners to be a person!). But people under 18 years old and people with intellectual disabilities can be directors \nof a non-profit of an organization whose purpose concerns them.  Check your by-laws and constitution \nto see if they set further restrictions. Sometimes, for example, a director must be a member of the orga-\nnization. In the case of federally incorporated non-profits that are soliciting corporations (described in the \nprevious section), at least two directors must be neither officers nor employees of the organization or its \naffiliates.\nNumber of board members. You must elect enough board directors to fill the number specified \nin your constitution. If the articles of incorporation of a federally incorporated non-profit specify a range, \nthen", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 0, "end_char_idx": 1091, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6af9a226-e325-4b58-8023-cd54d6189b9a": {"__data__": {"id_": "6af9a226-e325-4b58-8023-cd54d6189b9a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the eligibility requirements for directors, including being at least 18 years old, not currently bankrupt, and not having certain intellectual disabilities. It also mentions that directors must be \"natural persons\" and cannot be incorporated organizations. However, exceptions are made for individuals under 18 years old and those with intellectual disabilities to be directors of non-profits that concern them. The section also touches on the number of board members required, based on the organization's constitution or articles of incorporation for federally incorporated non-profits.", "next_section_summary": "The section discusses the importance of electing enough board directors to fill the specified number in the organization's constitution. It outlines the requirements for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits regarding the number of directors, with a minimum of three directors required for federally incorporated non-profits. The section also mentions the option to delegate the power to determine the number of directors to the board or membership. Additionally, it touches on the strategy of choosing an odd number of directors to avoid tie votes and the possibility of reserving seats on the board of directors in the organization's by-laws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements and considerations related to the board of directors of non-profit organizations. Key topics include the qualifications and restrictions for directors, the number of board members required, and the differences between federally and provincially incorporated non-profits in terms of board size regulations. The section also mentions the importance of checking the organization's by-laws and constitution for any additional restrictions on board membership.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for directors of federally incorporated non-profits that are soliciting corporations, in terms of their relationship to the organization and its affiliates?\n2. How can the number of board directors be determined for a federally incorporated non-profit if the articles of incorporation specify a range?\n3. What is the minimum number of directors required for a provincially incorporated non-profit, and how does this differ from the requirements for federally incorporated non-profits?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "ac5bfc30-5f3c-4e63-b0a4-076f4ecb92e5", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "61b06dedf2f2382418f022542ee256d90838b2bda94a54f00ed6c954ebc5c258", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "985eb033-290a-4c81-b79a-7eedf3466906", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "b2fcac15d66cf4d07d4ed828e7dc9febef046cfb4a07cb306113d9f472a470f5", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "3": {"node_id": "0cc78c02-616b-40bb-b93e-1721ce0c73d5", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {}, "hash": "cae766387096bbcdb659f3cbead2679d8206bd16fa8d1b68c62e51756dc90e9b", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "a non-profit of an organization whose purpose concerns them.  Check your by-laws and constitution \nto see if they set further restrictions. Sometimes, for example, a director must be a member of the orga-\nnization. In the case of federally incorporated non-profits that are soliciting corporations (described in the \nprevious section), at least two directors must be neither officers nor employees of the organization or its \naffiliates.\nNumber of board members. You must elect enough board directors to fill the number specified \nin your constitution. If the articles of incorporation of a federally incorporated non-profit specify a range, \nthen either the membership can fix the specific number of directors by resolution, which remains in effect \nuntil rescinded, or it can delegate this power to the board. In all cases, your organization must have a mini-\nmum of three directors, unless you are a non-soliciting, federally incorporated non-profit, in which case one \nis enough. Provincially incorporated non-profits can't establish a range: the size of the board is always a \nspecific number. A", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 444, "end_char_idx": 1544, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0cc78c02-616b-40bb-b93e-1721ce0c73d5": {"__data__": {"id_": "0cc78c02-616b-40bb-b93e-1721ce0c73d5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements and considerations related to the board of directors of non-profit organizations. Key topics include the qualifications and restrictions for directors, the number of board members required, and the differences between federally and provincially incorporated non-profits in terms of board size regulations. The section also mentions the importance of checking the organization's by-laws and constitution for any additional restrictions on board membership.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of the section include the size of the board of directors for provincially incorporated non-profits, the process for changing the number of seats on the board, the strategy of choosing an odd number of directors to avoid tie votes, the possibility of reserving seats for specific categories of people on the board, and the voting process for elections of directors. The section also mentions the ability of the board to fill vacancies that arise during the year. Key entities mentioned include provincially incorporated non-profits, the Registraire des entreprises, and the board of directors.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the importance of electing enough board directors to fill the specified number in the organization's constitution. It outlines the requirements for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits regarding the number of directors, with a minimum of three directors required for federally incorporated non-profits. The section also mentions the option to delegate the power to determine the number of directors to the board or membership. Additionally, it touches on the strategy of choosing an odd number of directors to avoid tie votes and the possibility of reserving seats on the board of directors in the organization's by-laws.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for the number of board directors in federally incorporated non-profits, and how can this number be determined or delegated?\n2. How do provincially incorporated non-profits differ in terms of establishing the size of their board of directors compared to federally incorporated non-profits?\n3. What is the significance of choosing an odd number of directors on a board to avoid tie votes, and how does this strategy impact decision-making within non-profit organizations?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_