Great, Not Just \nNecessary\u201d http://coco-net.org/making-your-agm-great-not-just-necessary/)\n\t\nCOCo encourages you to share and adapt the information in this info-sheet ac-\ncording to the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike license under which it \nis provided: creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5\nCOCo\u2019s info-sheets present only legal information, never advice. Please consult a lawyer to receive \nadvice that is appropriate to your situation and that accounts for any changes to the law since it was \npublished. You can contact COCo for a list of lawyers with experience working with community", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 352, "end_char_idx": 1336, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6effce94-61de-4d8e-b3bc-c016ee09f5c0": {"__data__": {"id_": "6effce94-61de-4d8e-b3bc-c016ee09f5c0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section covers important topics related to non-profit organizations, including the process of incorporating a non-profit in Quebec, generally accepted accounting principles for small non-profits, the roles and responsibilities of a board of directors, and tips on how to make your Annual General Meeting (AGM) great. The section also emphasizes the importance of consulting a lawyer for personalized advice and provides a Creative Commons license for sharing and adapting the information.", "section_summary": "This section provides legal information on Annual General Meetings (AGMs) and encourages sharing and adaptation of the information under a Creative Commons license. It emphasizes consulting a lawyer for advice tailored to individual situations and lists resources for finding lawyers experienced in working with community groups. The section also notes that while efforts are made to ensure accuracy, COCo assumes no responsibility for the use and interpretation of the information provided. The info-sheet was last updated in May 2018.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What is the Creative Commons license under which the information in the info-sheet is provided, and how does COCo encourage sharing and adaptation of the information?\n2. How does COCo emphasize the importance of consulting a lawyer for personalized advice tailored to individual situations when it comes to legal information on Annual General Meetings (AGMs)?\n3. What resources does COCo provide for finding lawyers experienced in working with community groups, and what disclaimer does COCo include regarding the accuracy and interpretation of the information provided in the info-sheet?"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "68af4cc8-3e54-4d69-a58a-92d81c3d9720", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "f12999a624456be353c1e718c4b3fcf335275b69ad37cfabfbaf8b71d97d068a", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}, "2": {"node_id": "df746b5e-e03e-41f5-bea3-65fbea3e9bcd", "node_type": "1", "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16"}, "hash": "5507c4b87317eccc924bb964940dca64ef6a28a6b538c4093b12fd8a0083720f", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_separator": "\n", "text": "http://coco-net.org/making-your-agm-great-not-just-necessary/)\n\t\nCOCo encourages you to share and adapt the information in this info-sheet ac-\ncording to the Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike license under which it \nis provided: creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5\nCOCo\u2019s info-sheets present only legal information, never advice. Please consult a lawyer to receive \nadvice that is appropriate to your situation and that accounts for any changes to the law since it was \npublished. You can contact COCo for a list of lawyers with experience working with community groups. \nWe work to ensure that all of the information in these info-sheets is accurate, but please know that COCo \nassumes no responsibility for your use and interpretation of the information.\nThis info-sheet was last updated on May 2018", "mimetype": "text/plain", "start_char_idx": 765, "end_char_idx": 1575, "metadata_seperator": "\n", "text_template": "[Excerpt from document]\n{metadata_str}\nExcerpt:\n-----\n{content}\n-----\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}}, "docstore/ref_doc_info": {"c631f355-dd41-4a54-9a7e-7aa87c241786": {"node_ids": ["07252161-1314-488a-8062-031ebdc040e1", "94cfbd58-17f6-400f-b97a-9510975d61e6", "652fc6b0-b8a0-4300-a9ba-b19a3cef3b43", "3838a706-6d9e-40e7-9465-ca531d1137cc"], "metadata": {"page_label": "1", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "next_section_summary": "The section emphasizes the importance of viewing meetings with members as opportunities to strengthen democratic processes within the organization and foster community relationships. It highlights the need to go beyond legal requirements and focus on creating spaces for self-reflection, critique, and collective power. The section also mentions resources from the Comit\u00e9 sectoriel de main-d\u2019\u0153uvre (CSMO) and an article on making AGMs more engaging and impactful.", "section_summary": "This section covers the importance of Annual General Meetings and Special General Meetings for non-profit organizations. It emphasizes the legal obligations for holding these meetings but also highlights the significance of these gatherings in strengthening democratic processes within the organization and allowing members to have a say in important decisions. The section also mentions the role of meetings in fostering relationships and providing space for self-reflection within community groups.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How does the document emphasize the importance of Annual General Meetings and Special General Meetings for non-profit organizations beyond just legal obligations?\n2. What resources are mentioned in the section for creating engaging and impactful Annual General Meetings?\n3. How does the document suggest that meetings with members can be used to strengthen democratic processes within an organization and foster community relationships?"}}, "60e5b871-41cd-4c67-9db9-2cd99c399ad6": {"node_ids": ["c367bbf7-45e6-488a-8ee0-d590e3c558a0", "622a5e29-7275-4d83-ad0f-54d591ef0f83", "5c3fe95d-d7d8-4d55-867e-e4890f2c1214", "c67fadbf-20e4-42e6-9c59-2d1331e6e954", "4d2b3101-3f19-4b3f-a7af-f5bbca645a3a"], "metadata": {"page_label": "2", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section provides information on the importance of holding general meetings, finding applicable rules, determining the timing for Annual General Meetings (AGM) and Special General Meetings (SGM), selecting a location for the meeting, setting the agenda, giving notice, establishing quorum, recording minutes, following meeting procedures, presenting financial statements, and conducting board elections. The content is likely sourced from the Comit\u00e9 sectoriel de main-d\u2019\u0153uvre (CSMO) and includes guidance on making AGMs effective and not just a necessary obligation.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of following the rules outlined in an organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and it sets out basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and office location. By-laws may also contain rules for running general meetings. Samples of valid by-laws for provincially incorporated organizations are provided in resources listed at the end of the document. For federally incorporated organizations, model by-laws and a by-laws builder are offered by Corporations Canada.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of knowing whether your non-profit organization is provincially or federally incorporated, as well as the rules set out in your organization's constitution and by-laws. It explains that the constitution is the document issued by the government certifying the organization's creation, and outlines basic rules such as the organization's name, purpose, and location.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the key differences between provincially incorporated non-profits in Quebec and federally incorporated non-profits in terms of the rules they must follow?\n2. How can non-profit organizations determine whether they are provincially or federally incorporated, and what implications does this have for their governance and operations?\n3. What specific information is typically included in a non-profit organization's constitution, and how does it differ from the organization's by-laws in terms of setting out rules and guidelines for governance?"}}, "e26213ae-5046-4ec1-933c-183e3635d301": {"node_ids": ["8eadf4d6-22b7-4f97-9cda-26c898111b68", "865a2a9c-caed-42cb-b2ef-2739c461704c", "2659ee8f-a62c-4a5a-8788-0849de5207fc"], "metadata": {"page_label": "3", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of by-laws for non-profit organizations, which are internal rules that govern how the organization operates. By-laws cover aspects such as membership meetings, board elections, and board meetings. They are different from organizational policies, which address day-to-day issues. By-laws must be approved by the membership and comply with the organization's constitution and the law under which it is incorporated. The section also mentions the requirement for a proportion of directors to have participated in the organization's activities to ensure decisions are made by those directly impacted.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the timing of Annual General Meetings (AGMs) and the importance of holding them within four months of the organization's financial year end. It also explains what a fiscal year is and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it mentions that some organizations have a fixed date for their AGM stated in their by-laws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses when to have your Annual General Meeting (AGM) if you are provincially incorporated. It mentions that provincially incorporated non-profits must hold their AGM at a time allowed by their letters patent and by-laws, or on the fourth Wednesday in January at their head office if no specific time is set. It also explains the concept of a fiscal year and how it is used by organizations to budget their spending and income. Additionally, it highlights the importance of holding the AGM within four months of the end of the organization's financial year to comply with legal requirements regarding financial statements.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for when a provincially incorporated non-profit organization must hold their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. How does the concept of a fiscal year relate to budgeting spending and income for organizations?\n3. Why is it important for financial statements presented at the AGM to have been approved within the last four months?"}}, "049dcf38-c1ad-4ff6-9c41-4a4872d17072": {"node_ids": ["1e4b0c7f-5e29-432a-8294-7f71fb03c15b", "66bc23f6-e5cf-40ca-b991-fad90828781d", "301e9186-10a1-433b-8029-a85c42ae6f7f"], "metadata": {"page_label": "4", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of fiscal (or financial) year, which is the year an organization uses to budget its spending and income. It explains that fiscal years vary from organization to organization, with examples of fiscal years running from January 1st to December 31st or April 1st to March 31st. The section also mentions the importance of having a fixed date for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) in the organization's bylaws, with examples of fixed dates or approximate timeframes for holding the AGM within four months of the end of the fiscal year.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) and a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains the consequences of not holding an AGM, the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM, and the importance of addressing emergent issues or decisions that require a formal vote. Additionally, it mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates for AGMs and provides information on the required proportion of votes for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations regarding their Annual General Meeting (AGM) and Special General Meeting (SGM). Key topics include the timing of AGMs, the consequences of not holding AGMs as required by federal law, and the ability of the Board of Directors to call an SGM at any time. The section also mentions that by-laws may further restrict the dates within which AGMs must be called. Key entities mentioned are federally incorporated non-profit organizations and interested persons who can apply for the dissolution of an organization that fails to hold AGMs as required.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific timing requirements for federally incorporated non-profit organizations to hold their Annual General Meetings (AGMs) according to federal law?\n2. What are the consequences for a federally incorporated organization that fails to hold an AGM as required by federal law for two consecutive years?\n3. How do the rules for calling Annual General Meetings (AGMs) differ between federally incorporated non-profit organizations and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations?"}}, "fdbf1e78-6297-4451-beae-74e92fd1de1f": {"node_ids": ["1d672a6c-6938-4276-9d22-5985f49dcc37", "15708724-884e-4a34-ad88-aa257eaa9152", "814d4744-3142-427a-87c5-de89592cd705", "928a02ed-66d6-430d-9a67-ce381ab764cb", "b4fc64c4-9bdb-4db4-bbd8-81148ce8c3d2"], "metadata": {"page_label": "5", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the concept of a Special General Meeting (SGM) for both provincially and federally incorporated organizations. It explains that an SGM can be called by the Board of Directors at any time for emergent issues or when the law requires a decision to be made at an SGM rather than an Annual General Meeting (AGM). It also provides information on the required proportion of votes needed for various decisions at general assemblies for provincially incorporated organizations, such as appointing an auditor, electing directors, and ratifying amendments to by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of removing a director before the end of their mandate at a company's Special General Meeting (SGM) with a 4/5 majority vote. It outlines the necessary steps, including providing notice to the director and allowing them to be heard at the meeting. The section also mentions the model language provided by the Registraire des enterprises for letters patent regarding the removal of a director. Additionally, it mentions the possibility of combining an SGM and an Annual General Meeting (AGM) for efficiency.", "section_summary": "This section outlines the decisions that require a vote at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting, such as changing the number of directors, amending letters patent, amalgamating with another organization, creating an executive committee, or dissolving the non-profit. It also specifies that certain decisions, like transforming the non-profit into a for-profit company or removing a director before the end of their mandate, require a specific majority vote at a Special General Meeting (SGM). The section also mentions the importance of having the necessary provisions in the letters patent or by-laws to confer the power to remove a director and outlines the process for doing so. The Registraire des enterprises provides model language for letters patent related to removing a director.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What decisions at a provincially incorporated organization's meeting require a specific majority vote at a Special General Meeting (SGM), such as transforming the non-profit into a for-profit company or removing a director before the end of their mandate?\n2. How can a director be removed before the end of their mandate at a company's Special General Meeting (SGM) with a 4/5 majority vote, and what steps need to be followed, including providing notice to the director and allowing them to be heard at the meeting?\n3. What model language does the Registraire des enterprises provide for letters patent regarding the removal of a director at a Special General Meeting (SGM) of a provincially incorporated organization, and what are the necessary provisions in the letters patent or by-laws to confer the power to remove a director?"}}, "f4067c9d-8cf5-4f23-8054-0ab044d048c8": {"node_ids": ["1d8de883-aee9-4bd1-bee8-b02ecf04c586", "677f8f01-4146-485d-b3f8-2fe85cf48cd6", "9c1da810-9064-4653-befd-804cd6a25fad", "de0d8147-eb0d-4914-8000-1bd0faebb104", "9a2525f1-5c26-4ae1-9da9-2f3bf96ecc0d"], "metadata": {"page_label": "6", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the process for calling a Special General Meeting (SGM) within an organization, the rights of members to request an SGM, and the potential actions members can take if the board is uncooperative in honoring the request. The entities involved are the organization's secretary, directors, members, and the Superior Court in the context of a mandamus request.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics covered in this section include the definition of a \"special resolution\" under federal non-profit law, the process for changing by-laws for provincially and federally incorporated organizations, and the decision-making process for certain matters in federally incorporated organizations such as removing a director, electing directors, and appointing or removing the organization's public accountant. The entities involved in these processes are the board of directors, members of the organization, and the public accountant.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements and procedures for federally incorporated non-profit organizations regarding special meetings of members (SGMs) and annual meetings of members. It explains that SGMs are where directors or the organization's public accountant can be removed by a simple majority, while all other decisions, including special resolutions, are made at annual meetings of members. Special resolutions require a 2/3 majority vote to pass. It also mentions that changes to bylaws for federally incorporated organizations can be made by the board and must be ratified by the membership at the next AGM or SGM.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What is the process for removing a director or the organization's public accountant in a federally incorporated non-profit organization?\n2. How are special resolutions defined and passed in federally incorporated non-profit organizations?\n3. What is the procedure for changing by-laws in both provincially and federally incorporated organizations, and how does it differ from other decision-making processes within the organization?"}}, "da58d603-ea36-41f1-858e-85ee40de5b74": {"node_ids": ["70107bbf-cfee-47f3-a8c7-843b91ea6291", "e2393b83-f7d2-4a44-add5-686d92876d6b", "008e03a3-f879-499d-a005-919f4660b853", "a95c6c7d-09a5-417e-9997-d110063c70ee", "560db0e8-332c-4163-a299-a0b14280c3cb"], "metadata": {"page_label": "7", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the key topics related to decision-making processes within a regulated non-profit or other legal entity. It covers the approval or ratification of certain actions such as dissolving or liquidating the organization's assets, approving contracts with potential conflicts of interest, holding meetings outside of Canada, adopting resolutions without a meeting, and deciding not to appoint a public accountant. The section also outlines the majority required for each decision, with some requiring a 2/3 majority and others needing a unanimous decision from all members.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses where to hold your annual general meeting (AGM) based on whether your organization is federally or provincially incorporated, as well as the requirements for setting the agenda for the meeting. It also mentions that directors typically set the agenda for general meetings, and special general meetings (SGMs) will address specific issues for which they were called.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the voting process for organizations with different classes of members, advising consultation of additional resources for more complex situations. It also addresses the location requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM), stating that federally incorporated organizations must hold their AGM in Canada, while provincially incorporated organizations must hold it in Quebec unless otherwise specified in their constitution or by-laws. The section suggests obtaining email confirmation from all members agreeing to hold the meeting elsewhere if necessary.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for holding an Annual General Meeting (AGM) for federally incorporated organizations in Canada?\n2. How can organizations with different classes of members navigate the voting process during meetings?\n3. What resources are recommended for organizations facing more complex decision-making processes, such as dissolving assets or approving contracts with conflicts of interest?"}}, "c398db93-c6b8-4247-a9c3-c7431bf61392": {"node_ids": ["732116b3-3008-46c2-ba14-44b7669ad01e", "72fe14e8-a15f-41d5-9d8e-f5fd39a6e5ea", "37c31f2a-8862-46a3-965f-85361fd0dc37", "844b5beb-57ee-45bb-a5c3-4fcbd3b393b3", "87558de9-a859-4360-a4e6-3f74d4a047a1"], "metadata": {"page_label": "8", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the approval of minutes from the previous year's AGM, presentation of activities over the past year, presentation of annual financial statements, presentation of accountant's report, and approval of financial statements. The entities involved in this section are the organization's Board, decision-makers, auditor or public accountant, and the membership.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the key topics and entities involved in an annual general meeting (AGM) for organizations. It covers the election of directors, voting on resolutions/contracts, addressing funders' concerns or questions, and discussing any other business (AOB) under a \"varia\" agenda. Provincially incorporated non-profits may have the ability to authorize the chair to reorder agenda items. It is also recommended to allow discussion on topics indicated by members.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the requirements for appointing an auditor or public accountant, voting on by-law/constitutional changes, electing new directors, voting on resolutions/contracts, addressing funders concerns or questions, and discussing any other business under the category of \"Varia.\" It also mentions the possibility of holding elections by mail or at a special general meeting for provincially incorporated non-profits.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can organizations address funders' concerns or questions during an annual general meeting (AGM)?\n2. What are the requirements for appointing an auditor or public accountant at an AGM for provincially incorporated non-profits or federally incorporated organizations?\n3. In what circumstances may elections for new directors be unnecessary at an AGM, according to the organization's by-laws or regulations for provincially incorporated non-profits?"}}, "282f2ba2-2d71-4884-85a1-e72053bfba44": {"node_ids": ["550bf8c1-4b13-43d6-8644-0e21989f498f", "082fbdfd-fa7c-4805-9a05-5aae704d8998", "87b37388-bd90-4eda-a56f-bac5b2e14fa0", "5f265ca5-8eed-44ee-b236-dad4973caf2e", "759401f7-7b24-4996-b6ec-bf9632493876"], "metadata": {"page_label": "9", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the legal requirements for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits regarding member proposals, written reasons for refusal, general meeting agendas, designated corporations, government subsidies, and the legitimacy of decisions in the eyes of the law.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the renouncement of the right to proper notice by members at a general meeting, as well as the requirements for giving notice for provincially incorporated organizations. It outlines the timeframe for giving notice, which is typically ten days before a general meeting, and the information that must be included in the notice, such as the time, place, and nature of the meeting. It also mentions that by-laws can specify the notice delay and that notice can be renounced by members.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of giving proper notice for general meetings in provincially incorporated non-profits. It mentions that failing to give notice can invalidate a meeting, but some by-laws may have provisions for this situation. Members can renounce their right to notice, allowing a meeting to proceed without delay. The section also addresses the timeframe for giving notice, stating that if not specified in the by-laws, notice must be given ten days before the meeting.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the consequences of failing to give proper notice for a general meeting in provincially incorporated non-profits, and how can these consequences be mitigated according to by-laws?\n2. How do members of a provincially incorporated non-profit renounce their right to proper notice for a general meeting, and what implications does this have for the meeting proceedings?\n3. In what ways do by-laws of provincially incorporated non-profits address the issue of renouncing notice for general meetings, and how does this impact the organization's ability to hold meetings efficiently and effectively?"}}, "f1da6ce9-7715-4589-af33-1241161c8917": {"node_ids": ["cb8722ba-db84-4e7b-8a5b-74c1b8d6311c", "a4fdd0a7-ac3e-4da4-81b7-3cc4f763c36d", "a78a3f1c-f7bc-4740-8640-58a636b76c77", "12a5b30d-3075-4da9-93d2-242db5097bff", "3c97f72f-6421-4d9b-82f1-56fe4b55d327", "4e9fd5f1-c437-458a-93aa-1c8c64d23400"], "metadata": {"page_label": "10", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for providing notice of meetings to members of a company or organization. It outlines the specific methods that must be used, such as sending notices by registered mail and advertising in newspapers. It also mentions that letters patent or by-laws may provide alternative methods for giving notice. The section emphasizes the importance of ensuring that the chosen method effectively reaches all members and warns against relying on simpler methods that may not be valid.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the various methods by which organizations can provide notice of meetings to their members, including electronic means, notice boards, publications, and newspapers. It also outlines the requirements for what must be included in the notice, as well as the option for organizations to request special permission from Corporations Canada for alternative notification methods.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for giving notice to members of federally incorporated organizations. It outlines the different methods of giving notice, such as by mail, courier, personal delivery, electronic communication, or publication in an organization's publication. The bylaws of the organization determine how notice must be given, and certain methods may be required based on the number of members in the organization.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific methods for giving notice to members of federally incorporated organizations, as outlined in the bylaws?\n2. How does the size of an organization impact the options available for providing notice of meetings to members?\n3. In what circumstances can federally incorporated organizations use electronic means to give notice to their members, and what alternative methods must be provided in conjunction with electronic communication?"}}, "1fd989f1-70ba-439a-a58d-93c39d17138c": {"node_ids": ["4e8b1b8e-b65e-4b35-9954-f6b3446ba6c6", "edadb228-5f50-4d63-919d-726c9fc830e6", "0ea387d1-2fb2-4fa4-99c5-507b9f99b639", "58eb867e-5f86-43b4-926e-d6483b3d51ca"], "metadata": {"page_label": "11", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the concept of a \"record date\" in relation to general meetings of a company, the authority of directors to set this date between 60 and 21 days before the meeting, and the implications for members in terms of receiving notice and voting rights based on their membership status on the record date. The section also highlights the legal requirements and options for setting a record date for notice and voting rights, as well as the default rules if the directors do not specify a record date. Key entities mentioned in this section are the directors of the company and the members who are affected by the record date decisions.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the importance of quorum in general meetings of non-profit organizations, ways to encourage membership participation, and the different ways quorum can be defined in the by-laws. The section also mentions that if quorum is not specified in the by-laws, it automatically becomes the majority of members with the right to vote. Additionally, it states that quorum for provincially incorporated non-profits can't be less than two people according to the law.", "section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the definition of quorum, its importance in ensuring the validity of a general meeting, and the potential frustration it may cause. It also discusses the purpose of quorum in preventing a small group of members from making decisions on behalf of the entire membership. Additionally, the section mentions that if quorum is not specified in the by-laws, it automatically becomes the majority of members with the right to vote. The section also touches on ways to encourage membership participation to ensure a healthy turnout for general meetings and foster communication.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How is quorum defined in the context of general meetings of non-profit organizations, and what is its significance in ensuring the validity of such meetings?\n2. What are the implications of not meeting the quorum requirement for a general meeting, and how does it impact the decision-making process within the organization?\n3. How can organizations encourage membership participation to ensure a healthy turnout for general meetings and foster effective communication among members?"}}, "cbd94be9-4790-4b77-8594-231c14b0f47d": {"node_ids": ["6b8017e9-f9f9-4145-9dde-9171d71b9408", "dc689839-dfe2-43a1-8c87-4abb0d66b4bb", "5326229c-5e0d-459e-b1a1-7cdadba0cdc5", "9efae872-19d6-48da-b3dc-d3a3ebec9e8e", "63971b82-0332-4461-8ac2-23d995087df5"], "metadata": {"page_label": "12", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the concept of quorum for non-profit organizations, stating that provincially incorporated non-profits must have a minimum quorum of two people, while federally incorporated non-profits can have a meeting with just one person. It also addresses whether quorum needs to be maintained throughout a meeting, with by-laws determining the requirements. Additionally, it mentions that notice is not required to resume a meeting adjourned for a specified time of 30 days or less.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of recording and storing minutes of general meetings for organizations. It highlights the need to document voting results, resolutions, and declarations made by the meeting chair. The section also emphasizes the requirement to store minutes with other corporate records at the head office, or as designated for federally incorporated non-profits. It specifies the signing of minutes by designated individuals for provincially incorporated non-profits and outlines member access to meeting minutes and reports. Additionally, it mentions that the board of such organizations decides on granting access to meeting minutes upon request.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the importance of meeting minutes as a written summary of key points and decisions made during a meeting. It emphasizes the need to record who gave presentations, the substance of decisions, and the names of directors elected. It also mentions the importance of recording for and against each decision, as well as the number of abstentions. The section highlights the storage of minutes with other corporate records at the head office and the recording of signed resolutions made in lieu of a general meeting.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How should meeting minutes be structured to effectively summarize key points and decisions made during a meeting?\n2. What information should be included in meeting minutes, such as details on presentations, decisions, and elected directors?\n3. Where should meeting minutes be stored for both provincially and federally incorporated non-profit organizations, and what are the requirements for storing signed resolutions made in lieu of a general meeting?"}}, "a4ba6f22-7643-483b-bb82-856847715c65": {"node_ids": ["873a2a6a-8000-4603-bb04-6b4a53bc9ca1", "3bc55f24-cd7d-4028-81cf-632e4d265f00", "48903e9e-8e30-40dd-ab10-6c04419f034d", "0460fb5f-798d-4d58-9878-52f0da01c66e"], "metadata": {"page_label": "13", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the importance of choosing the right chair for a meeting, considering factors such as the potential divisiveness of the issues, the organization's principles, personality, and purpose. It also outlines the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization, including ensuring valid notice of the meeting and the protocol for selecting a chair if none is specified in the by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the voting procedures for federally and provincially incorporated non-profits during meetings. It discusses the default voting procedure for federally incorporated non-profits, which is by show of hands unless a member requests a vote by secret ballot. It also mentions that for federal non-profits, a member can request a vote by secret ballot even after a vote by show of hands has taken place. For provincially incorporated non-profits, the chair decides on the voting procedure if not specified in the by-laws, with a common practice being a vote by show of hands unless a member requests a secret ballot before the vote.", "section_summary": "This section covers the process of choosing a meeting secretary, checking quorum, establishing rules of procedure, voting on the adoption of the meeting agenda, and the different forms of agenda items (plenary and deliberative). It also discusses the voting procedures for provincially and federally incorporated non-profits, including the default voting procedure for federally incorporated non-profits and the option for a member to request a vote by secret ballot.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the responsibilities of the chair of a provincially incorporated organization in terms of establishing rules of procedure for general meetings if not specified in the by-laws?\n2. How are agenda items categorized in meetings for provincially and federally incorporated non-profits, and what is the process for voting on the adoption of the meeting agenda?\n3. In what circumstances can a member of a federally incorporated non-profit request a vote by secret ballot instead of the default voting procedure of voting by show of hands?"}}, "95ff3021-55b1-42ae-9b84-01244ed6cb72": {"node_ids": ["6e104a0e-1d75-476c-b1f5-69c9a2360968", "6a71c415-c6a3-411c-b9fb-7aa375a08428", "5d96a1e5-d631-4c1a-9f80-bb065c175f50", "0446c746-0a39-4bc5-b2b5-91b17dcebbf7", "3660c50d-f632-4e87-accd-6ff1258fcc46", "fee81634-74cb-4104-9582-ef8dd5c97a70"], "metadata": {"page_label": "14", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of voting during meetings, including the option of requesting a secret ballot, different methods of voting such as spoken or standing/sitting, and the flexibility organizations have in adapting or creating their own meeting procedures. It also mentions that formal rules of procedure, such as Robert's Rules of Order, may not always be necessary for small non-profits, and suggests considering a simplified set of rules.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include voting procedures for members of non-profit organizations, including the power of the chair to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie, the ability to adopt resolutions with unanimous consent, and the flexibility in voting methods for federally incorporated non-profits. The entities mentioned are members, chairs, and Corporations Canada.", "section_summary": "The section discusses the voting procedures for provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to hold director elections by mail and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent. It also mentions the power of the meeting chair to propose motions, vote on motions, and cast a deciding vote in case of a tie. Additionally, it highlights the flexibility in voting for federally incorporated non-profits, allowing for voting by members who are not physically present through technological or electronic means.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can provincially incorporated non-profits hold director elections and adopt resolutions with unanimous consent?\n2. What voting rights and powers does the meeting chair have in provincially incorporated non-profits, including the ability to cast a deciding vote in case of a tie?\n3. In what ways do federally incorporated non-profits offer more flexibility in voting for members who are not physically present, such as through technological or electronic means?"}}, "768dc53f-9953-42ac-9ac8-20cfbce559d1": {"node_ids": ["7bebe7da-55c3-4d02-ab55-512d89eafa08", "842bd02e-bc0c-4bb0-a6c6-0179ee07d3e3", "22a929c5-011e-49b2-99b9-ed030773cf2a", "1e0a8995-6dde-453a-93ca-61778f126a5e"], "metadata": {"page_label": "15", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the validity of written resolutions in federally incorporated non-profits, the limitations on passing resolutions in provincially incorporated non-profits, the ability to adjust voting requirements in by-laws, and the option for federal non-profits to make decisions by consensus. The section also mentions the importance of defining consensus, verifying its attainment, and providing a process for voting on issues where consensus cannot be reached. The entities involved in this section are federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the accounting procedures and financial statement requirements for provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It emphasizes the importance of accurate financial statements and mentions that the law sets minimum levels of analysis, but organizations may have additional requirements in their by-laws or from funders. The financial statements required for the Annual General Meeting (AGM) include a balance sheet and may also include a general statement of income and expenditure. Provincially incorporated organizations must also present any financial information required by their constitution.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the different levels of accounting analysis that can be applied to financial statements: compilation, financial review, and audit. It also mentions the minimum levels of analysis required by law and the possibility of needing a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements. Additionally, it highlights the requirement for provincially incorporated organizations to present a balance sheet at their AGM, with the period covered ending no more than four months before the meeting.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the three levels of accounting analysis that financial statements can be subjected to, and how do they differ in terms of rigor and assurance of accuracy?\n2. What are the minimum levels of analysis required by law for financial statements, and what factors may require a more rigorous analysis based on by-laws, letters patent, or funder requirements?\n3. For provincially incorporated non-profit organizations, what financial statements are required to be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM), and what is the timeframe for the information covered in the balance sheet?"}}, "3b056607-e0c2-4906-8634-a50be5a38bc0": {"node_ids": ["38458d4b-1110-4e8f-9dff-4484a143463a", "b18a487e-2d70-40a4-94a5-8c176283b5b2", "4ec2240c-2233-4d62-80f4-c70fc23787b2", "2ef4a3c4-0f38-4749-a39e-a98d4eb1f4e9"], "metadata": {"page_label": "16", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the presentation of a statement of income and expenditure, financial information required by the organization's constitution or by-laws, approval by the current board, and the attachment and presentation of an auditor's report if applicable. The section also mentions the possibility of extending the deadline for submitting financial information to six months for organizations based outside of Quebec. Key entities involved are provincially incorporated organizations, the current board of directors, and auditors.", "next_section_summary": "The key topics of this section include the requirements for federally incorporated non-profits to submit comparative financial statements that conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by CPA Canada. The information must be approved by the current board and signed by a director before being submitted to the AGM. If the organization has named a public accountant, their report must also be attached and presented. Failure to comply with these requirements is considered an offence. Additionally, there are additional obligations related to financial statements for non-profit subsidiaries.", "section_summary": "This section provides information for federally incorporated non-profits on the financial statements that must be presented at the Annual General Meeting (AGM). The required financial statements include a balance sheet, statements of comprehensive income or retained earnings, changes in equity or income, and cash flows or changes in financial position. These statements must be comparative, covering the previous two financial years. Additionally, any financial information required by the organization's constitution, by-laws, and member agreements must be presented. The financial statements must conform to generally accepted accounting principles established by Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada. Approval by the current board and signature by a director are required before submission to the AGM. If a public accountant was named by the organization, their report must also be included.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific financial statements that federally incorporated non-profits must present at their Annual General Meeting (AGM)?\n2. What are the requirements for the approval and submission of financial information by federally incorporated non-profits, as outlined in the document?\n3. How does the document specify the role of Chartered Professional Accountants (CPA) Canada in establishing generally accepted accounting principles for federally incorporated non-profits?"}}, "7bf252ee-0804-439c-bd5c-c4af7eb9683b": {"node_ids": ["433abf83-d941-4f6b-a2f9-95f1ef45c91d", "55aabf50-2db9-442d-b9a1-3bad13f54918", "97b0d192-5c95-4986-99f1-62484d5e4a7c", "62368369-8298-4ab4-805c-bf687399a535", "9d0644fc-ee2b-4249-b7af-de5af7b8fd5c"], "metadata": {"page_label": "17", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements for presenting financial information at annual general meetings (AGMs) for federally incorporated organizations. It mentions that financial statements must be approved and signed, and if applicable, accompanied by a public accountant's report. It also outlines specific requirements for federally incorporated non-profits, such as sending members copies or summaries of financial documents and providing access to full copies at no cost. Additionally, it suggests ways to streamline this process, such as notifying members that documents are available at the organization's head office for free.", "next_section_summary": "This section outlines the categories of federally incorporated non-profits based on their soliciting status and gross annual revenue. It also discusses the requirements for naming a public accountant and the intensity of review by the accountant based on revenue thresholds. Additionally, it touches on board elections and the length of director terms, highlighting the option to have longer terms specified in the organization's bylaws.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the level of scrutiny required for federally incorporated non-profits based on their gross annual income and whether they are considered a \"soliciting corporation\". It outlines the requirements for different categories of non-profits in terms of naming a public accountant and the intensity of review by the accountant. The section also mentions the definition of \"public sources\" and directs readers to Corporations Canada's website for more information. Key entities mentioned include federally incorporated non-profits, public accountants, and Corporations Canada.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the specific requirements for federally incorporated non-profits in terms of naming a public accountant and the intensity of review by the accountant based on their gross annual revenue and soliciting status?\n2. How does the level of scrutiny required for federally incorporated non-profits vary based on their gross annual income and whether they are considered a \"soliciting corporation\"?\n3. What options do members of federally incorporated non-profits have in terms of choosing between a review engagement and an audit by a public accountant, depending on the organization's gross annual revenue and soliciting status?"}}, "ac5bfc30-5f3c-4e63-b0a4-076f4ecb92e5": {"node_ids": ["985eb033-290a-4c81-b79a-7eedf3466906", "6af9a226-e325-4b58-8023-cd54d6189b9a", "0cc78c02-616b-40bb-b93e-1721ce0c73d5", "0b15bde9-60e8-40ac-8bf4-f9814db5cc99", "8c7c3774-7205-4067-941d-7096ce15dc9a", "eed4f553-c0c2-466d-9e68-d7e52a4a5002"], "metadata": {"page_label": "18", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "The section discusses the election and term limits for directors in federally and provincially incorporated non-profit organizations. It explains that in federally incorporated non-profits, a director's term ends at the close of the following AGM if the length of the term is not specified. For provincially incorporated non-profits, directors must retire yearly but can be eligible for re-election. The section also mentions that directors can be re-elected indefinitely unless term limits are set in the organization's by-laws.", "next_section_summary": "This section discusses the requirements and considerations related to the board of directors of non-profit organizations. Key topics include the qualifications and restrictions for directors, the number of board members required, and the differences between federally and provincially incorporated non-profits in terms of board size regulations. The section also mentions the importance of checking the organization's by-laws and constitution for any additional restrictions on board membership.", "section_summary": "This section discusses the eligibility requirements for directors, including being at least 18 years old, not currently bankrupt, and not having certain intellectual disabilities. It also mentions that directors must be \"natural persons\" and cannot be incorporated organizations. However, exceptions are made for individuals under 18 years old and those with intellectual disabilities to be directors of non-profits that concern them. The section also touches on the number of board members required, based on the organization's constitution or articles of incorporation for federally incorporated non-profits.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What are the eligibility requirements for directors in non-profit organizations, including age restrictions, bankruptcy status, and intellectual disabilities?\n2. Are there any exceptions to the eligibility requirements for directors, such as for individuals under 18 years old or those with intellectual disabilities?\n3. How does the number of board members required in a non-profit organization relate to the organization's constitution or articles of incorporation, especially for federally incorporated non-profits with specified ranges?"}}, "369ede98-a66e-4554-94da-87bfc2409dda": {"node_ids": ["1879f495-1380-4fde-8c71-059207dd982c", "892b1b73-f36b-4cb0-9a50-3938cd65eebf", "e5465a85-1306-4dad-a54b-81b462253fee", "1f28210b-b998-406f-8c07-a1cd6e8767b3"], "metadata": {"page_label": "19", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the process of filling vacancies on a board of directors, the importance of holding elections at an AGM, and the rules for removing board members. It emphasizes the need for quorum to fill vacancies, the requirement to hold elections at AGMs, and the necessity of outlining removal procedures in the by-laws or letters patent. The section also references additional information on holding Special General Meetings and the incorporation of non-profits in Quebec.", "next_section_summary": "This section provides information on legal resources for non-profit organizations, specifically focusing on their rights, duties, and responsibilities. It references a guide by Paul Martel on the subject, as well as a toolbox on democratic governance for non-profit organizations in the community and social economy sector. The section also mentions a specific tool on the legal structure of non-profit organizations and democratic governance. Overall, the key topics covered in this section include legal rights and responsibilities of non-profit organizations, democratic governance, and the legal structure of non-profit organizations.", "section_summary": "This section provides further resources and legal notices related to non-profit governance. It includes information on resources available for administrators and members of associations, as well as a guide on the rights, duties, and responsibilities of administrators of non-profit organizations. The resources mentioned are primarily in French and can be borrowed from COCo's resource library or purchased from them. The section also mentions a toolbox on democratic governance for non-profit organizations in community action.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. What resources are available for administrators and members of non-profit associations in Quebec, and where can they be accessed?\n2. What guide provides information on the rights, duties, and responsibilities of administrators of non-profit organizations in Quebec?\n3. Where can non-profit organizations in the community and social economy sector find a toolbox on democratic governance specifically tailored to their needs?"}}, "68af4cc8-3e54-4d69-a58a-92d81c3d9720": {"node_ids": ["f1c3907f-778f-421a-bbed-bb505e760efb", "df746b5e-e03e-41f5-bea3-65fbea3e9bcd", "6effce94-61de-4d8e-b3bc-c016ee09f5c0"], "metadata": {"page_label": "20", "file_name": "AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_path": "data\\dev\\docs\\AGM-Legal-Info-Sheet-EN-2019.pdf", "file_type": "application/pdf", "file_size": 432341, "creation_date": "2025-02-16", "last_modified_date": "2025-02-16", "prev_section_summary": "This section discusses the legal structure of non-profit organizations (NPOs) and democratic governance. It references resources such as the Comit\u00e9 sectoriel de main-d\u2019\u0153uvre \u2013 \u00c9conomie sociale action communautaire (CSMO-ESAC) and Corporations Canada website for information on NPO governance, members meetings, and model by-laws. The key topics covered include the structure of NPOs, governance practices, and legal requirements for NPOs.", "next_section_summary": "This section covers important topics related to non-profit organizations, including the process of incorporating a non-profit in Quebec, generally accepted accounting principles for small non-profits, the roles and responsibilities of a board of directors, and tips on how to make your Annual General Meeting (AGM) great. The section also emphasizes the importance of consulting a lawyer for personalized advice and provides a Creative Commons license for sharing and adapting the information.", "section_summary": "This section provides links to resources on the Corporations Canada website for bylaw building and requirements for soliciting corporations under the Canada Not-for-profit Corporations Act. It also mentions other info-sheets released by COCo related to the incorporation of non-profits in Quebec, accounting principles for small non-profits, roles and responsibilities of the board of directors, and tips for making AGMs great. The section encourages sharing and adapting these resources.", "questions_this_excerpt_can_answer": "1. How can non-profit organizations in Quebec incorporate themselves and what are the generally accepted accounting principles for small non-profits?\n2. What are the roles and responsibilities of a board of directors in a non-profit organization, and how can one make their Annual General Meeting (AGM) great?\n3. Where can one find resources and information on bylaw building and requirements for soliciting corporations under the Canada Not-for-profit Corporations Act, as well as other related info-sheets released by COCo?"}}}}
